# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: calculus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:calculus/calculus] Calculus is the "mathematical backbone" for solving problems in which variable quantities change with time or another reference value.
[src:calculus/calculus] It has also been called "the basic instrument of physical science".
[src:calculus/calculus] In the late 17th century, Isaac Newton and Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz each independently formulated infinitesimal calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] Later work, including the formalization of the concept of limits, put calculus on a more solid conceptual footing.
[src:calculus/calculus] The concepts and techniques of calculus have broad applications in science, engineering, and other branches of mathematics.
[src:calculus/calculus] In Latin, the word *calculus* means "pebble" – a meaning which still persists in medicine.
[src:calculus/calculus] Because pebbles were used as counters in Roman counting-board abacuses, Romans called their reckoning "placing pebbles" (*calculos ponere*), and would settle accounts by "calling someone to the pebbles" (*vocare aliquem ad calculos*); the Latin word *calculare* appeared around 400 AD in Spain.
[src:calculus/calculus] The word *calculate* was used in English in this sense at least as early as 1672, several years before the publications of Leibniz and Newton, who wrote their mathematical texts in Latin.
[src:calculus/calculus] In addition to differential calculus and integral calculus, the term is also used for naming specific methods of computation or theories that imply some sort of computation.
[src:calculus/calculus] Examples of this usage include propositional calculus, Ricci calculus, calculus of variations, lambda calculus, sequent calculus, and process calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] Furthermore, the term *calculus* has variously been applied in ethics and philosophy, for such systems as Bentham's felicific calculus, and the ethical calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] Calculus provides a generalization of concepts from elementary geometry and algebra.
[src:calculus/calculus] For example, instead of describing the slope of a straight line, calculus can describe the changing slope of a complicated curve.
[src:calculus/calculus] Elementary geometry provides formulas for the area of shapes like triangles, squares, and other polygons, whereas calculus provides a way to find the area of a shape whose boundary is described by a complicated formula.
[src:calculus/calculus] In elementary algebra, one can calculate the distance traveled over time by an object moving at a constant velocity, while in calculus, one can calculate the distance that an object travels even when the velocity varies.
[src:calculus/calculus] Calculus is usually developed by working with very small quantities.
[src:calculus/calculus] Historically, the first method of doing so was by infinitesimals.
[src:calculus/calculus] These are objects which can be treated like real numbers but which are, in some sense, "infinitely small".
[src:calculus/calculus] For example, an infinitesimal number could be greater than 0, but less than any number in the sequence 1, 1/2, 1/3, ... and thus less than any positive real number.
[src:calculus/calculus] From this point of view, calculus is a collection of techniques for manipulating infinitesimals.
[src:calculus/calculus] Suppose there is a function, like the ratio ⁠ ${\tfrac {\sin x}{x}}$ ⁠, which cannot be defined at zero.
[src:calculus/calculus] However, as x becomes closer and closer to zero, ⁠ ${\tfrac {\sin x}{x}}$ ⁠ becomes arbitrarily close to 1.
[src:calculus/calculus] In other words, the limit of ⁠ ${\tfrac {\sin x}{x}},$ ⁠ as x approaches zero, equals 1.
[src:calculus/calculus] The infinitesimal approach fell out of favor in the 19th century because it was difficult to make the notion of an infinitesimal precise.
[src:calculus/calculus] In the late 19th century, infinitesimals were replaced within academia by the epsilon, delta approach to limits.
[src:calculus/calculus] Limits describe the behavior of a function at a certain input in terms of its values at nearby inputs.
[src:calculus/calculus] They capture small-scale behavior using the intrinsic structure of the real number system.
[src:calculus/calculus] In this treatment, calculus is a collection of techniques for manipulating certain limits.
[src:calculus/calculus] Infinitesimals get replaced by sequences of smaller and smaller numbers, and the infinitely small behavior of a function is found by taking the limiting behavior for these sequences.
[src:calculus/calculus] Limits were thought to provide a more rigorous foundation for calculus, and for this reason, they became the standard approach during the 20th century.
[src:calculus/calculus] However, the infinitesimal concept was revived in the 20th century with the introduction of non-standard analysis and smooth infinitesimal analysis, which provided solid foundations for the manipulation of infinitesimals.
[src:calculus/calculus] Differential calculus is the study of the definition, properties, and applications of the derivative of a function.
[src:calculus/calculus] The process of finding the derivative is called *differentiation*.
[src:calculus/calculus] Given a function and a point in the domain, the derivative at that point is a way of encoding the small-scale behavior of the function near that point.
[src:calculus/calculus] By finding the derivative of a function at every point in its domain, it is possible to produce a new function, called the *derivative function* or just the *derivative* of the original function.
[src:calculus/calculus] Geometrically speaking, the derivative generalizes the idea of the slope of a line: it gives a way to quantify the steepness of the graph of a function, even when that graph is not a straight line.
[src:calculus/calculus] In Lagrange's notation, the symbol for a derivative is an apostrophe-like mark called a prime.
[src:calculus/calculus] Thus, the derivative of a function called *f* is denoted by *f′*, pronounced "f prime" or "f dash".
[src:calculus/calculus] For instance, if *f*(*x*) = *x*2 is the squaring function, then *f′*(*x*) = 2*x* is its derivative.
[src:calculus/calculus] This gives an exact value for the slope of a straight line.
[src:calculus/calculus] If the graph of the function is not a straight line, however, then the change in *y* divided by the change in *x* varies.
[src:calculus/calculus] Derivatives give an exact meaning to the notion of change in output concerning change in input.
[src:calculus/calculus] To be concrete, let *f* be a function, and fix a point *a* in the domain of *f*.
[src:calculus/calculus] (*a*, *f*(*a*)) is a point on the graph of the function.
[src:calculus/calculus] If *h* is a number close to zero, then *a* + *h* is a number close to *a*.
[src:calculus/calculus] This expression is called a *difference quotient*.
[src:calculus/calculus] A line through two points on a curve is called a *secant line*, so *m* is the slope of the secant line between (*a*, *f*(*a*)) and (*a* + *h*, *f*(*a* + *h*)).
[src:calculus/calculus] The secant line is only an approximation to the behavior of the function at the point *a* because it does not account for what happens between *a* and *a* + *h*.
[src:calculus/calculus] It is not possible to discover the behavior at *a* by setting *h* to zero because this would require dividing by zero, which is undefined.
[src:calculus/calculus] Geometrically, the derivative is the slope of the tangent line to the graph of *f* at *a*.
[src:calculus/calculus] The tangent line is a limit of secant lines just as the derivative is a limit of difference quotients.
[src:calculus/calculus] If the input of the function represents time, then the derivative represents change concerning time.
[src:calculus/calculus] For example, if *f* is a function that takes time as input and gives the position of a ball at that time as output, then the derivative of *f* is how the position is changing in time, that is, it is the velocity of the ball.
[src:calculus/calculus] In an approach based on limits, the symbol ⁠*dy*/*dx*⁠ is to be interpreted not as the quotient of two numbers but as a shorthand for the limit computed above.
[src:calculus/calculus] Leibniz, however, did intend it to represent the quotient of two infinitesimally small numbers, *dy* being the infinitesimally small change in *y* caused by an infinitesimally small change *dx* applied to *x*.
[src:calculus/calculus] We can also think of ⁠*d*/*dx*⁠ as a differentiation operator, which takes a function as an input and gives another function, the derivative, as the output.
[src:calculus/calculus] In this usage, the *dx* in the denominator is read as "with respect to *x*".
[src:calculus/calculus] A sequence of midpoint Riemann sums over a regular partition of an interval: the total area of the rectangles converges to the integral of the function.
[src:calculus/calculus] A motivating example is the distance traveled in a given time.
[src:calculus/calculus] But if the speed changes, a more powerful method of finding the distance is necessary.
[src:calculus/calculus] One such method is to approximate the distance traveled by breaking up the time into many short intervals of time, then multiplying the time elapsed in each interval by one of the speeds in that interval, and then taking the sum (a Riemann sum) of the approximate distance traveled in each interval.
[src:calculus/calculus] The basic idea is that if only a short time elapses, then the speed will stay more or less the same.
[src:calculus/calculus] However, a Riemann sum only gives an approximation of the distance traveled.
[src:calculus/calculus] We must take the limit of all such Riemann sums to find the exact distance traveled.
[src:calculus/calculus] When velocity is constant, the total distance traveled over the given time interval can be computed by multiplying velocity and time.
[src:calculus/calculus] For example, traveling a steady 50 mph for 3 hours results in a total distance of 150 miles.
[src:calculus/calculus] Plotting the velocity as a function of time yields a rectangle with a height equal to the velocity and a width equal to the time elapsed.
[src:calculus/calculus] Therefore, the product of velocity and time also calculates the rectangular area under the (constant) velocity curve.
[src:calculus/calculus] This connection between the area under a curve and the distance traveled can be extended to *any* irregularly shaped region exhibiting a fluctuating velocity over a given period.
[src:calculus/calculus] If *f*(*x*) represents speed as it varies over time, the distance traveled between the times represented by *a* and *b* is the area of the region between *f*(*x*) and the *x*-axis, between *x* = *a* and *x* = *b*.
[src:calculus/calculus] To approximate that area, an intuitive method would be to divide up the distance between *a* and *b* into several equal segments, the length of each segment represented by the symbol Δ*x*.
[src:calculus/calculus] For each small segment, we can choose one value of the function *f*(*x*).
[src:calculus/calculus] Then the area of the rectangle with base Δ*x* and height *h* gives the distance (time Δ*x* multiplied by speed *h*) traveled in that segment.
[src:calculus/calculus] Associated with each segment is the average value of the function above it, *f*(*x*) = *h*.
[src:calculus/calculus] The sum of all such rectangles gives an approximation of the area between the axis and the curve, which is an approximation of the total distance traveled.
[src:calculus/calculus] A smaller value for Δ*x* will give more rectangles and in most cases a better approximation, but for an exact answer, we need to take a limit as Δ*x* approaches zero.
[src:calculus/calculus] The symbol of integration is $\int$ , an elongated *S* chosen to suggest summation.
[src:calculus/calculus] and is read "the integral from *a* to *b* of *f*-of-*x* with respect to *x*." The Leibniz notation *dx* is intended to suggest dividing the area under the curve into an infinite number of rectangles so that their width Δ*x* becomes the infinitesimally small *dx*.
[src:calculus/calculus] Functions differing by only a constant have the same derivative, and it can be shown that the antiderivative of a given function is a family of functions differing only by a constant.
[src:calculus/calculus] The unspecified constant *C* present in the indefinite integral or antiderivative is known as the constant of integration.
[src:calculus/calculus] The fundamental theorem of calculus states that differentiation and integration are inverse operations.
[src:calculus/calculus] More precisely, it relates the values of antiderivatives to definite integrals.
[src:calculus/calculus] Because it is usually easier to compute an antiderivative than to apply the definition of a definite integral, the fundamental theorem of calculus provides a practical way of computing definite integrals.
[src:calculus/calculus] It can also be interpreted as a precise statement of the fact that differentiation is the inverse of integration.
[src:calculus/calculus] This realization, made by both Newton and Leibniz, was key to the proliferation of analytic results after their work became known.
[src:calculus/calculus] It is also a prototype solution of a differential equation.
[src:calculus/calculus] Differential equations relate an unknown function to its derivatives and are ubiquitous in the sciences.
[src:calculus/calculus] Multivariable calculus is the extension of calculus in one variable to functions of several variables: the differentiation and integration of functions involving multiple variables (*multivariate*), rather than just one.
[src:calculus/calculus] It is used extensively in physics and engineering, especially in the description of electromagnetic fields, gravitational fields, and fluid flow.
[src:calculus/calculus] A differential equation is an equation that relates one or more unknown functions and their derivatives.
[src:calculus/calculus] In applications, the functions generally represent physical quantities, the derivatives represent their rates of change, and the differential equation defines a relationship between the two.
[src:calculus/calculus] Such relations are common in mathematical models and scientific laws; therefore, differential equations play a prominent role in many disciplines including engineering, physics, economics, and biology.
[src:calculus/calculus] For example, the differential equation ${\frac {df}{dt}}=-af(t)$ is solved by a function $f(t)$ that is proportional to its own derivative.
[src:calculus/calculus] Any such function has the form $f(t)=Ce^{-at},$ where C is a constant.
[src:calculus/calculus] This differential equation describes exponential decay.
[src:calculus/calculus] The study of differential equations consists mainly of the study of their solutions (the set of functions that satisfy each equation), and of the properties of their solutions.
[src:calculus/calculus] Real analysis provides the rigorous underpinnings of calculus, establishing that ideas often introduced heuristically in introductory calculus have a solid foundation.
[src:calculus/calculus] It studies the behavior of real numbers, sequences and series of real numbers, and real functions.
[src:calculus/calculus] Some particular properties of real-valued sequences and functions that real analysis studies include convergence, limits, continuity, smoothness, differentiability, and integrability.
[src:calculus/calculus] Complex analysis investigates functions of a complex variable.
[src:calculus/calculus] It is helpful in many branches of mathematics, including real analysis, algebraic geometry, number theory, analytic combinatorics, and applied mathematics, as well as in physics, including the branches of hydrodynamics, thermodynamics, quantum mechanics, and twistor theory.
[src:calculus/calculus] By extension, use of complex analysis also has applications in engineering fields such as nuclear, aerospace, mechanical and electrical engineering.
[src:calculus/calculus] Complex analysis studies holomorphic functions, the differentiable functions of a complex variable.
[src:calculus/calculus] By contrast with the real case, a holomorphic function is always infinitely differentiable and equal to the sum of its Taylor series in some neighborhood of each point of its domain.
[src:calculus/calculus] This makes methods and results of complex analysis significantly different from those of real analysis.
[src:calculus/calculus] The calculus of variations (or *variational calculus*) studies functionals in analogy to how elementary calculus studies functions.
[src:calculus/calculus] Whereas elementary calculus considers infinitesimally small changes in the input and output values of functions, the calculus of variations considers infinitesimally small changes in functions themselves.
[src:calculus/calculus] A functional is a mapping from a set of functions to the real numbers.
[src:calculus/calculus] The calculus of variations studies how the output of a functional changes as the input function is infinitesimally perturbed.
[src:calculus/calculus] A simple example of such a problem is to find the curve of shortest length connecting two points.
[src:calculus/calculus] If there are no constraints, the solution is a straight line between the points.
[src:calculus/calculus] However, if the curve is constrained to lie on a surface in space, then the solution is less obvious, and possibly many solutions may exist.
[src:calculus/calculus] Such solutions are known as *geodesics*.
[src:calculus/calculus] A related problem is posed by Fermat's principle: light follows the path of shortest optical length connecting two points, which depends upon the material of the medium.
[src:calculus/calculus] One corresponding concept in mechanics is the principle of least/stationary action.
[src:calculus/calculus] Functionals are often expressed as definite integrals involving functions and their derivatives.
[src:calculus/calculus] Functions that maximize or minimize functionals may be found using the Euler–Lagrange equation of the calculus of variations.
[src:calculus/calculus] Modern calculus was developed in 17th-century Europe by Isaac Newton and Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz (independently of each other, first publishing around the same time).
[src:calculus/calculus] Elements of it first appeared in ancient Egypt and later Greece, then in China and the Middle East, and still later again in medieval Europe and India.
[src:calculus/calculus] Calculations of volume and area, one goal of integral calculus, can be found in the Egyptian Moscow papyrus (c.
[src:calculus/calculus] 1820 BC), but the formulae are simple instructions, with no indication as to how they were obtained.
[src:calculus/calculus] Babylonians may have discovered the trapezoidal rule while doing astronomical observations of Jupiter.
[src:calculus/calculus] Laying the foundations for integral calculus and foreshadowing the concept of the limit, ancient Greek mathematician Eudoxus of Cnidus (c.
[src:calculus/calculus] 390–337 BC) developed the method of exhaustion to prove the formulas for cone and pyramid volumes.
[src:calculus/calculus] During the Hellenistic period, this method was further developed by Archimedes (c.
[src:calculus/calculus] 212 BC), who combined it with a concept of the indivisibles—a precursor to infinitesimals—allowing him to solve several problems now treated by integral calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] In *The Method of Mechanical Theorems* he describes, for example, calculating the center of gravity of a solid hemisphere, the center of gravity of a frustum of a circular paraboloid, and the area of a region bounded by a parabola and one of its secant lines.
[src:calculus/calculus] The method of exhaustion was later discovered independently in China by Liu Hui in the 3rd century AD to find the area of a circle.
[src:calculus/calculus] In the 5th century AD, Zu Gengzhi, son of Zu Chongzhi, established a method that would later be called Cavalieri's principle to find the volume of a sphere.
[src:calculus/calculus] In the Middle East, Hasan Ibn al-Haytham, Latinized as Alhazen (c.
[src:calculus/calculus] 1040 AD) derived a formula for the sum of fourth powers.
[src:calculus/calculus] He used the results to carry out what would now be called an integration of this function, where the formulae for the sums of integral squares and fourth powers allowed him to calculate the volume of a paraboloid.
[src:calculus/calculus] 1114–1185) was acquainted with some ideas of differential calculus, and devised a way of working with infinitesimals applied to trigonometry.
[src:calculus/calculus] In the 14th century, Indian mathematicians gave a non-rigorous method, resembling differentiation, applicable to some trigonometric functions.
[src:calculus/calculus] Madhava of Sangamagrama and the Kerala School of Astronomy and Mathematics stated components of calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] The mathematical study of continuity was revived in the 14th century by the Oxford Calculators and French collaborators such as Nicole Oresme, who proved the divergence of the harmonic series; both are also credited with formulating the mean speed theorem.
[src:calculus/calculus] Johannes Kepler's work *Stereometria Doliorum* (1615) formed the basis of integral calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] Kepler developed a method to calculate the area of an ellipse by adding up the lengths of many radii drawn from a focus of the ellipse.
[src:calculus/calculus] Bonaventura Cavalieri, basing his work on Kepler's, argued that volumes and areas should be computed as the sums of the volumes and areas of infinitesimally thin cross-sections.
[src:calculus/calculus] The formal study of calculus brought together Cavalieri's infinitesimals with the calculus of finite differences developed in Europe at around the same time.
[src:calculus/calculus] Pierre de Fermat, claiming that he borrowed from Diophantus, introduced the concept of adequality, which represented equality up to an infinitesimal error term.
[src:calculus/calculus] The combination was achieved by John Wallis, Isaac Barrow, and James Gregory, the latter two proving part of the fundamental theorem of calculus around 1670.
[src:calculus/calculus] The product rule and chain rule, the notions of higher derivatives and Taylor series, and of analytic functions were used by Isaac Newton in an idiosyncratic notation which he applied to solve problems of mathematical physics.
[src:calculus/calculus] In his works, Newton rephrased his ideas to suit the mathematical idiom of the time, replacing calculations with infinitesimals by equivalent geometrical arguments that were considered beyond reproach.
[src:calculus/calculus] He used the methods of calculus to solve the problem of planetary motion, the shape of the surface of a rotating fluid, the oblateness of the earth, the motion of a weight sliding on a cycloid, and many other problems discussed in his *Principia Mathematica* (1687).
[src:calculus/calculus] In other work, he developed series expansions for functions, including fractional and irrational powers, and it was clear that he understood the principles of the Taylor series.
[src:calculus/calculus] He did not publish all these discoveries, and at this time, infinitesimal methods were still considered disreputable.
[src:calculus/calculus] was the first to state clearly the rules of calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] These ideas were arranged into a true calculus of infinitesimals by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, who was originally accused of plagiarism by Newton.
[src:calculus/calculus] He is now regarded as an independent inventor of and contributor to calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] His contribution was to provide a clear set of rules for working with infinitesimal quantities, allowing the computation of second and higher derivatives, and providing the product rule and chain rule, in their differential and integral forms.
[src:calculus/calculus] Unlike Newton, Leibniz put painstaking effort into his choices of notation.
[src:calculus/calculus] Today, Newton and Leibniz are usually both given credit for independently inventing and developing calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] Newton was the first to apply calculus to general physics.
[src:calculus/calculus] Leibniz developed much of the notation used in calculus today.
[src:calculus/calculus] When Newton and Leibniz first published their results, there was great controversy over which mathematician (and therefore which country) deserved credit.
[src:calculus/calculus] Newton derived his results first in 1665-1666 (later to be published in his *Method of Fluxions*), but Leibniz published his "Nova Methodus pro Maximis et Minimis" first in 1684.
[src:calculus/calculus] Newton claimed Leibniz stole ideas from his unpublished notes, which Newton had shared with a few members of the Royal Society.
[src:calculus/calculus] This controversy divided English-speaking mathematicians from continental European mathematicians for many years, to the detriment of English mathematics.
[src:calculus/calculus] A careful examination of the papers of Leibniz and Newton shows that they arrived at their results independently, with Leibniz starting first with integration and Newton with differentiation.
[src:calculus/calculus] It is Leibniz, however, who gave the new discipline its name.
[src:calculus/calculus] Newton called his calculus "the science of fluxions", a term that endured in English schools into the 19th century.
[src:calculus/calculus] The first complete treatise on calculus to be written in English and use the Leibniz notation was not published until 1815.
[src:calculus/calculus] Since the time of Newton and Leibniz, many mathematicians have contributed to the continuing development of calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] One of the first and most complete works on both infinitesimal and integral calculus was written in 1748 by Maria Gaetana Agnesi.
[src:calculus/calculus] In calculus, *foundations* refers to the rigorous development of the subject from axioms and definitions.
[src:calculus/calculus] In early calculus, the use of infinitesimal quantities was thought unrigorous and was fiercely criticized by several authors, most notably Michel Rolle and Bishop Berkeley.
[src:calculus/calculus] Berkeley famously described infinitesimals as the ghosts of departed quantities in his book *The Analyst* in 1734.
[src:calculus/calculus] Working out a rigorous foundation for calculus occupied mathematicians for much of the century following Newton and Leibniz.
[src:calculus/calculus] Several mathematicians, including Maclaurin, tried to prove the soundness of using infinitesimals, but it would not be until 150 years later when, due to the work of Cauchy and Weierstrass, a way was finally found to avoid mere "notions" of infinitely small quantities.
[src:calculus/calculus] The foundations of differential and integral calculus had been laid.
[src:calculus/calculus] In Cauchy's *Cours d'Analyse*, we find a broad range of foundational approaches, including a definition of continuity in terms of infinitesimals, and a (somewhat imprecise) prototype of an (ε, δ)-definition of limit in the definition of differentiation.
[src:calculus/calculus] In his work, Weierstrass formalized the concept of limit and eliminated infinitesimals (although his definition can validate nilsquare infinitesimals).
[src:calculus/calculus] Following the work of Weierstrass, it eventually became common to base calculus on limits instead of infinitesimal quantities, though the subject is still occasionally called "infinitesimal calculus".
[src:calculus/calculus] Bernhard Riemann used these ideas to give a precise definition of the integral.
[src:calculus/calculus] It was also during this period that the ideas of calculus were generalized to the complex plane with the development of complex analysis.
[src:calculus/calculus] In modern mathematics, the foundations of calculus are included in the field of real analysis, which contains full definitions and proofs of the theorems of calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] The reach of calculus has also been greatly extended.
[src:calculus/calculus] Henri Lebesgue invented measure theory, based on earlier developments by Émile Borel, and used it to define integrals of all but the most pathological functions.
[src:calculus/calculus] Laurent Schwartz introduced distributions, which can be used to take the derivative of any function whatsoever.
[src:calculus/calculus] Limits are not the only rigorous approach to the foundation of calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] Another way is to use Abraham Robinson's non-standard analysis.
[src:calculus/calculus] Robinson's approach, developed in the 1960s, uses technical machinery from mathematical logic to augment the real number system with infinitesimal and infinite numbers, as in the original Newton-Leibniz conception.
[src:calculus/calculus] The resulting numbers are called hyperreal numbers, and they can be used to give a Leibniz-like development of the usual rules of calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] There is also smooth infinitesimal analysis, which differs from non-standard analysis in that it mandates neglecting higher-power infinitesimals during derivations.
[src:calculus/calculus] Lawvere and employing the methods of category theory, smooth infinitesimal analysis views all functions as being continuous and incapable of being expressed in terms of discrete entities.
[src:calculus/calculus] One aspect of this formulation is that the law of excluded middle does not hold.
[src:calculus/calculus] The law of excluded middle is also rejected in constructive mathematics, a branch of mathematics that insists that proofs of the existence of a number, function, or other mathematical object should give a construction of the object.
[src:calculus/calculus] Reformulations of calculus in a constructive framework are generally part of the subject of constructive analysis.
[src:calculus/calculus] While many of the ideas of calculus had been developed earlier in Greece, China, India, Iraq, Persia, and Japan, the use of calculus began in Europe, during the 17th century, when Newton and Leibniz built on the work of earlier mathematicians to introduce its basic principles.
[src:calculus/calculus] Applications of differential calculus include computations involving velocity and acceleration, the slope of a curve, and optimization.
[src:calculus/calculus] Applications of integral calculus include computations involving area, volume, arc length, center of mass, work, and pressure.
[src:calculus/calculus] More advanced applications include power series and Fourier series.
[src:calculus/calculus] Calculus is also used to gain a more precise understanding of the nature of space, time, and motion.
[src:calculus/calculus] For centuries, mathematicians and philosophers wrestled with paradoxes involving division by zero or sums of infinitely many numbers.
[src:calculus/calculus] These questions arise in the study of motion and area.
[src:calculus/calculus] The ancient Greek philosopher Zeno of Elea gave several famous examples of such paradoxes.
[src:calculus/calculus] Calculus provides tools, especially the limit and the infinite series, that resolve the paradoxes.
[src:calculus/calculus] Calculus is used in every branch of the physical sciences, actuarial science, computer science, statistics, engineering, economics, business, medicine, demography, and in other fields wherever a problem can be mathematically modeled and an optimal solution is desired.
[src:calculus/calculus] It allows one to go from (non-constant) rates of change to the total change or vice versa, and many times in studying a problem we know one and are trying to find the other.
[src:calculus/calculus] Calculus can be used in conjunction with other mathematical disciplines.
[src:calculus/calculus] For example, it can be used with linear algebra to find the "best fit" linear approximation for a set of points in a domain.
[src:calculus/calculus] Or, it can be used in probability theory to determine the expectation value of a continuous random variable given a probability density function.
[src:calculus/calculus] In analytic geometry, the study of graphs of functions, calculus is used to find high points and low points (maxima and minima), slope, concavity, inflection points, area under curves, and area between curves.
[src:calculus/calculus] Calculus is also used to find approximate solutions to equations; in practice, it is the standard way to solve differential equations and do root finding in most applications.
[src:calculus/calculus] Examples are methods such as Newton's method, fixed point iteration, and linear approximation.
[src:calculus/calculus] For instance, spacecraft use a variation of the Euler method to approximate curved courses within zero-gravity environments.
[src:calculus/calculus] Physics makes particular use of calculus; all concepts in classical mechanics and electromagnetism are related through calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] The mass of an object of known density, the moment of inertia of objects, and the potential energies due to gravitational and electromagnetic forces can all be found by the use of calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] An example of the use of calculus in mechanics is Newton's second law of motion, which states that the derivative of an object's momentum concerning time equals the net force upon it.
[src:calculus/calculus] Alternatively, Newton's second law can be expressed by saying that the net force equals the object's mass times its acceleration, which is the time derivative of velocity and thus the second time derivative of spatial position.
[src:calculus/calculus] Starting from knowing how an object is accelerating, we use calculus to derive its path.
[src:calculus/calculus] Maxwell's theory of electromagnetism and Einstein's theory of general relativity are also expressed in the language of differential calculus.
[src:calculus/calculus] Differential equations are likewise prominent in quantum mechanics.
[src:calculus/calculus] Chemistry also uses calculus, for example in determining reaction rates and in studying radioactive decay.
[src:calculus/calculus] In biology, population dynamics starts with reproduction and death rates to model population changes.
[src:calculus/calculus] In the realm of medicine, calculus can be used in many ways, from predicting the optimal branching angle of a blood vessel to maximize flow, to understanding how quickly a drug is eliminated from a body or how quickly a cancerous tumor grows.
[src:calculus/calculus] In economics, calculus allows for the determination of maximal profit by providing a way to easily calculate both marginal cost and marginal revenue.
[src:calculus/calculus] The Black–Scholes model, a central concept in option pricing, employs a differential equation.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In calculus, the **chain rule** is a formula that expresses the derivative of the composition of two differentiable functions z and y in terms of the derivatives of z and y.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The chain rule may also be expressed in Leibniz's notation.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] If a variable z depends on the variable y, which itself depends on the variable x (that is, y and z are dependent variables), then z depends on x as well, via the intermediate variable y.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In this case, the chain rule is expressed as ${\frac {dz}{dx}}={\frac {dz}{dy}}\cdot {\frac {dy}{dx}},$ and $\left.{\frac {dz}{dx}}\right|_{x}=\left.{\frac {dz}{dy}}\right|_{y(x)}\cdot \left.{\frac {dy}{dx}}\right|_{x},$ for indicating at which points the derivatives have to be evaluated.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In integration, the counterpart to the chain rule is the substitution rule.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Intuitively, the chain rule states that knowing the instantaneous rate of change of *z* relative to *y* and that of *y* relative to *x* allows one to calculate the instantaneous rate of change of *z* relative to *x* as the product of the two rates of change.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The relationship between this example and the chain rule is as follows.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Let z, y and x be the (variable) positions of the car, the bicycle, and the walking man, respectively.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The chain rule seems to have first been used by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] He used it to calculate the derivative of ${\sqrt {a+bz+cz^{2}}}$ as the composite of the square root function and the function $a+bz+cz^{2}\!$ .
[src:calculus/chain-rule] He first mentioned it in a 1676 memoir (with a sign error in the calculation).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The common notation of the chain rule is due to Leibniz.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Guillaume de l'Hôpital used the chain rule implicitly in his *Analyse des infiniment petits*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The chain rule does not appear in any of Leonhard Euler's analysis books, even though they were written over a hundred years after Leibniz's discovery.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] It is believed that the first "modern" version of the chain rule appears in Lagrange's 1797 *Théorie des fonctions analytiques*; it also appears in Cauchy's 1823 *Résumé des Leçons données a L’École Royale Polytechnique sur Le Calcul Infinitesimal*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The simplest form of the chain rule is for real-valued functions of one real variable.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The chain rule can be applied to composites of more than two functions.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] To take the derivative of a composite of more than two functions, notice that the composite of f, g, and *h* (in that order) is the composite of f with *g* ∘ *h*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The chain rule states that to compute the derivative of *f* ∘ *g* ∘ *h*, it is sufficient to compute the derivative of *f* and the derivative of *g* ∘ *h*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The derivative of f can be calculated directly, and the derivative of *g* ∘ *h* can be calculated by applying the chain rule again.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Another way of computing this derivative is to view the composite function *f* ∘ *g* ∘ *h* as the composite of *f* ∘ *g* and *h*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] This is the same as what was computed above.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Sometimes, it is necessary to differentiate an arbitrarily long composition of the form $f_{1}\circ f_{2}\circ \cdots \circ f_{n-1}\circ f_{n}\!$ .
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The chain rule can be used to derive some well-known differentiation rules.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] For example, the quotient rule is a consequence of the chain rule and the product rule.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] To compute the derivative of 1/*g*(*x*), notice that it is the composite of g with the reciprocal function, that is, the function that sends x to 1/*x*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The derivative of the reciprocal function is $-1/x^{2}\!$ .
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Suppose that *y* = *g*(*x*) has an inverse function.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Call its inverse function f so that we have *x* = *f*(*y*).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] There is a formula for the derivative of f in terms of the derivative of g.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] And because the functions $f(g(x))$ and x are equal, their derivatives must be equal.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The derivative of x is the constant function with value 1, and the derivative of $f(g(x))$ is determined by the chain rule.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] To express f' as a function of an independent variable y, we substitute $f(y)$ for x wherever it appears.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] For example, consider the function *g*(*x*) = *e**x*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] This formula is true whenever g is differentiable and its inverse f is also differentiable.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] This formula can fail when one of these conditions is not true.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Its inverse is *f*(*y*) = *y*1/3, which is not differentiable at zero.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] If we attempt to use the above formula to compute the derivative of f at zero, then we must evaluate 1/*g*′(*f*(0)).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Since *f*(0) = 0 and *g*′(0) = 0, we must evaluate 1/0, which is undefined.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Therefore, the formula fails in this case.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] This is not surprising because f is not differentiable at zero.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The chain rule forms the basis of the backpropagation algorithm, which is used in gradient descent of neural networks in deep learning (artificial intelligence).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Faà di Bruno's formula generalizes the chain rule to higher derivatives.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Assume for the moment that $g(x)\!$ does not equal $g(a)$ for any x near a .
[src:calculus/chain-rule] If g oscillates near a, then it might happen that no matter how close one gets to a, there is always an even closer x such that *g*(*x*) = *g*(*a*).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] For example, this happens near *a* = 0 for the continuous function g defined by *g*(*x*) = 0 for *x* = 0 and *g*(*x*) = *x*2 sin(1/*x*) otherwise.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Whenever this happens, the above expression is undefined because it involves division by zero.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Whenever *g*(*x*) is not equal to *g*(*a*), this is clear because the factors of *g*(*x*) − *g*(*a*) cancel.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] When *g*(*x*) equals *g*(*a*), then the difference quotient for *f* ∘ *g* is zero because *f*(*g*(*x*)) equals *f*(*g*(*a*)), and the above product is zero because it equals *f*′(*g*(*a*)) times zero.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] So the above product is always equal to the difference quotient, and to show that the derivative of *f* ∘ *g* at *a* exists and to determine its value, we need only show that the limit as *x* goes to *a* of the above product exists and determine its value.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] To do this, recall that the limit of a product exists if the limits of its factors exist.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] When this happens, the limit of the product of these two factors will equal the product of the limits of the factors.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The latter is the difference quotient for g at a, and because g is differentiable at a by assumption, its limit as x tends to a exists and equals *g*′(*a*).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] As for *Q*(*g*(*x*)), notice that *Q* is defined wherever *f* is.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Furthermore, *f* is differentiable at *g*(*a*) by assumption, so *Q* is continuous at *g*(*a*), by definition of the derivative.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The function g is continuous at a because it is differentiable at a, and therefore *Q* ∘ *g* is continuous at a.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] This shows that the limits of both factors exist and that they equal *f*′(*g*(*a*)) and *g*′(*a*), respectively.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Another way of proving the chain rule is to measure the error in the linear approximation determined by the derivative.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] This proof has the advantage that it generalizes to several variables.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In the situation of the chain rule, such a function *ε* exists because *g* is assumed to be differentiable at *a*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Again by assumption, a similar function also exists for *f* at *g*(*a*).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Calling this function *η*, we have $f(g(a)+k)-f(g(a))=f'(g(a))k+\eta (k)k.$ The above definition imposes no constraints on *η*(0), even though it is assumed that *η*(*k*) tends to zero as *k* tends to zero.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] If we set *η*(0) = 0, then *η* is continuous at 0.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Proving the theorem requires studying the difference *f*(*g*(*a* + *h*)) − *f*(*g*(*a*)) as *h* tends to zero.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The first step is to substitute for *g*(*a* + *h*) using the definition of differentiability of *g* at *a*: $f(g(a+h))-f(g(a))=f(g(a)+g'(a)h+\varepsilon (h)h)-f(g(a)).$ The next step is to use the definition of differentiability of *f* at *g*(*a*).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] This requires a term of the form *f*(*g*(*a*) + *k*) for some *k*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In the above equation, the correct *k* varies with *h*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Applying the definition of the derivative gives: $f(g(a)+k_{h})-f(g(a))=f'(g(a))k_{h}+\eta (k_{h})k_{h}.$ To study the behavior of this expression as *h* tends to zero, expand *k**h*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] After regrouping the terms, the right-hand side becomes: $f'(g(a))g'(a)h+[f'(g(a))\varepsilon (h)+\eta (k_{h})g'(a)+\eta (k_{h})\varepsilon (h)]h.$ Because *ε*(*h*) and *η*(*k**h*) tend to zero as *h* tends to zero, the first two bracketed terms tend to zero as *h* tends to zero.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Applying the same theorem on products of limits as in the first proof, the third bracketed term also tends zero.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Because the above expression is equal to the difference *f*(*g*(*a* + *h*)) − *f*(*g*(*a*)), by the definition of the derivative *f* ∘ *g* is differentiable at *a* and its derivative is *f*′(*g*(*a*)) *g*′(*a*).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The role of *Q* in the first proof is played by *η* in this proof.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] They are related by the equation: $Q(y)=f'(g(a))+\eta (y-g(a)).$ The need to define *Q* at *g*(*a*) is analogous to the need to define *η* at zero.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Constantin Carathéodory's alternative definition of the differentiability of a function can be used to give an elegant proof of the chain rule.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Under this definition, a function f is differentiable at a point a if and only if there is a function q, continuous at a and such that *f*(*x*) − *f*(*a*) = *q*(*x*)(*x* − *a*).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] There is at most one such function, and if f is differentiable at a then *f* ′(*a*) = *q*(*a*).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] This method of factoring also allows a unified approach to stronger forms of differentiability, when the derivative is required to be Lipschitz continuous, Hölder continuous, etc.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Differentiation itself can be viewed as the polynomial remainder theorem (the little Bézout theorem, or factor theorem), generalized to an appropriate class of functions.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The full generalization of the chain rule to multi-variable functions (such as $f\colon \mathbb {R} ^{m}\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ) is rather technical.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] As this case occurs often in the study of functions of a single variable, it is worth describing it separately.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Let $f\colon \mathbb {R} ^{k}\to \mathbb {R}$ , and $g_{i}\colon \mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R}$ for each $i=1,2,\dots ,k.$ To write the chain rule for the composition of functions $x\mapsto f(g_{1}(x),\dots ,g_{k}(x)),$ one needs the partial derivatives of f with respect to its k arguments.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The usual notations for partial derivatives involve names for the arguments of the function.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] As these arguments are not named in the above formula, it is simpler and clearer to use *D*-Notation, and to denote by $D_{i}f$ the partial derivative of f with respect to its ith argument, and by $D_{i}f(z)$ the value of this derivative at z.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The simplest way for writing the chain rule in the general case is to use the total derivative, which is a linear transformation that captures all directional derivatives in a single formula.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] These two derivatives are linear transformations **R***n* → **R***m* and **R***m* → **R***k*, respectively, so they can be composed.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Because the total derivative is a linear transformation, the functions appearing in the formula can be rewritten as matrices.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The matrix corresponding to a total derivative is called a Jacobian matrix, and the composite of two derivatives corresponds to the product of their Jacobian matrices.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] That is, the Jacobian of a composite function is the product of the Jacobians of the composed functions (evaluated at the appropriate points).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The higher-dimensional chain rule is a generalization of the one-dimensional chain rule.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In the language of linear transformations, *D**a*(*g*) is the function which scales a vector by a factor of *g*′(*a*) and *D**g*(*a*)(*f*) is the function which scales a vector by a factor of *f*′(*g*(*a*)).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The chain rule says that the composite of these two linear transformations is the linear transformation *D**a*(*f* ∘ *g*), and therefore it is the function that scales a vector by *f*′(*g*(*a*))⋅*g*′(*a*).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The chain rule for total derivatives implies a chain rule for partial derivatives.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Recall that when the total derivative exists, the partial derivative in the i-th coordinate direction is found by multiplying the Jacobian matrix by the i-th basis vector.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In the special case where *k* = 1, so that *f* is a real-valued function, then this formula simplifies even further: ${\frac {\partial y}{\partial x_{i}}}=\sum _{\ell =1}^{m}{\frac {\partial y}{\partial u_{\ell }}}{\frac {\partial u_{\ell }}{\partial x_{i}}}.$ This can be rewritten as a dot product.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] Faà di Bruno's formula for higher-order derivatives of single-variable functions generalizes to the multivariable case.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] All extensions of calculus have a chain rule.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In most of these, the formula remains the same, though the meaning of that formula may be vastly different.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In this situation, the chain rule represents the fact that the derivative of *f* ∘ *g* is the composite of the derivative of *f* and the derivative of *g*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] This theorem is an immediate consequence of the higher dimensional chain rule given above, and it has exactly the same formula.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The chain rule is also valid for Fréchet derivatives in Banach spaces.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] This case and the previous one admit a simultaneous generalization to Banach manifolds.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In differential algebra, the derivative is interpreted as a morphism of modules of Kähler differentials.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] A ring homomorphism of commutative rings *f* : *R* → *S* determines a morphism of Kähler differentials *Df* : Ω*R* → Ω*S* which sends an element *dr* to *d*(*f*(*r*)), the exterior differential of *f*(*r*).
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The formula *D*(*f* ∘ *g*) = *Df* ∘ *Dg* holds in this context as well.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The common feature of these examples is that they are expressions of the idea that the derivative is part of a functor.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] A functor is an operation on spaces and functions between them.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] It associates to each space a new space and to each function between two spaces a new function between the corresponding new spaces.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In each of the above cases, the functor sends each space to its tangent bundle and it sends each function to its derivative.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] For example, in the manifold case, the derivative sends a *C**r*-manifold to a *C**r*−1-manifold (its tangent bundle) and a *C**r*-function to its total derivative.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] There is one requirement for this to be a functor, namely that the derivative of a composite must be the composite of the derivatives.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] There are also chain rules in stochastic calculus.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] One of these, Itō's lemma, expresses the composite of an Itō process (or more generally a semimartingale) *dX**t* with a twice-differentiable function *f*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] In Itō's lemma, the derivative of the composite function depends not only on *dX**t* and the derivative of *f* but also on the second derivative of *f*.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] The dependence on the second derivative is a consequence of the non-zero quadratic variation of the stochastic process, which broadly speaking means that the process can move up and down in a very rough way.
[src:calculus/chain-rule] This variant of the chain rule is not an example of a functor because the two functions being composed are of different types.
[src:calculus/derivative] of the tangent line is equal to the derivative of the function at the marked point.
[src:calculus/derivative] The derivative at different points of a differentiable function.
[src:calculus/derivative] In mathematics, the **derivative** is a fundamental tool that quantifies the sensitivity to change of a function's output with respect to its input.
[src:calculus/derivative] The derivative of a function of a single variable at a chosen input value, when it exists, is the slope of the tangent line to the graph of the function at that point.
[src:calculus/derivative] The tangent line is the best linear approximation of the function near that input value.
[src:calculus/derivative] The derivative is often described as the **instantaneous rate of change**, the ratio of the instantaneous change in the dependent variable to that of the independent variable.
[src:calculus/derivative] The process of finding a derivative is called **differentiation**.
[src:calculus/derivative] There are multiple different notations for differentiation.
[src:calculus/derivative] *Leibniz notation*, named after Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, is represented as the ratio of two differentials, whereas *prime notation* is written by adding a prime mark.
[src:calculus/derivative] Higher order notations represent repeated differentiation, and they are usually denoted in Leibniz notation by adding superscripts to the differentials, and in prime notation by adding additional prime marks.
[src:calculus/derivative] Higher order derivatives are used in physics; for example, the first derivative with respect to time of the position of a moving object is its velocity, and the second derivative is its acceleration.
[src:calculus/derivative] Derivatives can be generalized to functions of several real variables.
[src:calculus/derivative] In this case, the derivative is reinterpreted as a linear transformation whose graph is (after an appropriate translation) the best linear approximation to the graph of the original function.
[src:calculus/derivative] The Jacobian matrix is the matrix that represents this linear transformation with respect to the basis given by the choice of independent and dependent variables.
[src:calculus/derivative] It can be calculated in terms of the partial derivatives with respect to the independent variables.
[src:calculus/derivative] For a real-valued function of several variables, the Jacobian matrix reduces to the gradient vector.
[src:calculus/derivative] A function of a real variable $f(x)$ is differentiable at a point a of its domain, if its domain contains an open interval containing ⁠ a ⁠, and the limit $L=\lim _{h\to 0}{\frac {f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}}$ exists.
[src:calculus/derivative] This is an example of the (ε, δ)-definition of limit.
[src:calculus/derivative] If the function f is differentiable at ⁠ a ⁠, that is if the limit L exists, then this limit is called the *derivative* of f at ⁠ a ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] Multiple notations for the derivative exist.
[src:calculus/derivative] The derivative of f at a can be denoted ⁠ $f'(a)$ ⁠, read as "⁠ f ⁠ prime of ⁠ a ⁠"; or it can be denoted ⁠ $\textstyle {\frac {df}{dx}}(a)$ ⁠, read as "the derivative of f with respect to x at ⁠ a ⁠" or "⁠ $df$ ⁠ by (or over) $dx$ at ⁠ a ⁠".
[src:calculus/derivative] If f is a function that has a derivative at every point in its domain, then a function can be defined by mapping every point x to the value of the derivative of f at ⁠ x ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] This function is written $f'$ and is called the *derivative function* or the *derivative of* ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] The function f sometimes has a derivative at most, but not all, points of its domain.
[src:calculus/derivative] The function whose value at a equals $f'(a)$ whenever $f'(a)$ is defined and elsewhere is undefined is also called the derivative of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] It is still a function, but its domain may be smaller than the domain of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] For example, let f be the squaring function: ⁠ $f(x)=x^{2}$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] The closer h is to ⁠ 0 ⁠, the closer this expression becomes to the value ⁠ $2a$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] The limit exists, and for every input a the limit is ⁠ $2a$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] So, the derivative of the squaring function is the doubling function: ⁠ $f'(x)=2x$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] The ratio in the definition of the derivative is the slope of the line through two points on the graph of the function ⁠ f ⁠, specifically the points $(a,f(a))$ and ⁠ $(a+h,f(a+h))$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] As h is made smaller, these points grow closer together, and the slope of this line approaches the limiting value, the slope of the tangent to the graph of f at ⁠ a ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] In other words, the derivative is the slope of the tangent.
[src:calculus/derivative] One way to think of the derivative ${\textstyle {\frac {df}{dx}}(a)}$ is as the ratio of an infinitesimal change in the output of the function f to an infinitesimal change in its input.
[src:calculus/derivative] In order to make this intuition rigorous, a system of rules for manipulating infinitesimal quantities is required.
[src:calculus/derivative] The system of hyperreal numbers is a way of treating infinite and infinitesimal quantities.
[src:calculus/derivative] The hyperreals are an extension of the real numbers that contain numbers greater than anything of the form $1+1+\cdots +1$ for any finite number of terms.
[src:calculus/derivative] Such numbers are infinite, and their reciprocals are infinitesimals.
[src:calculus/derivative] The application of hyperreal numbers to the foundations of calculus is called nonstandard analysis.
[src:calculus/derivative] This provides a way to define the basic concepts of calculus such as the derivative and integral in terms of infinitesimals, thereby giving a precise meaning to the d in the Leibniz notation.
[src:calculus/derivative] Thus, the derivative of $f(x)$ becomes $f'(x)=\operatorname {st} \left({\frac {f(x+dx)-f(x)}{dx}}\right)$ for an arbitrary infinitesimal ⁠ $dx$ ⁠, where $\operatorname {st}$ denotes the standard part function, which "rounds off" each finite hyperreal to the nearest real.
[src:calculus/derivative] since the tangent slopes do not approach the same value from the left as they do from the right.
[src:calculus/derivative] If f is differentiable at ⁠ a ⁠, then f must also be continuous at ⁠ a ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] As an example, choose a point a and let f be the step function that returns the value 1 for all x less than ⁠ a ⁠, and returns a different value 10 for all x greater than or equal to ⁠ a ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] The function f cannot have a derivative at ⁠ a ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] If h is negative, then $a+h$ is on the low part of the step, so the secant line from a to $a+h$ is very steep; as h tends to zero, the slope tends to infinity.
[src:calculus/derivative] If h is positive, then $a+h$ is on the high part of the step, so the secant line from a to $a+h$ has slope zero.
[src:calculus/derivative] Consequently, the secant lines do not approach any single slope, so the limit of the difference quotient does not exist.
[src:calculus/derivative] However, even if a function is continuous at a point, it may not be differentiable there.
[src:calculus/derivative] For example, the absolute value function given by $f(x)=|x|$ is continuous at ⁠ $x=0$ ⁠, but it is not differentiable there.
[src:calculus/derivative] If h is positive, then the slope of the secant line from 0 to h is one; if h is negative, then the slope of the secant line from 0 to h is ⁠ $-1$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] This can be seen graphically as a "kink" or a "cusp" in the graph at ⁠ $x=0$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] Even a function with a smooth graph is not differentiable at a point where its tangent is vertical: For instance, the function given by $f(x)=x^{1/3}$ is not differentiable at ⁠ $x=0$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] In summary, a function that has a derivative is continuous, but there are continuous functions that do not have a derivative.
[src:calculus/derivative] Most functions that occur in practice have derivatives at all points or almost every point.
[src:calculus/derivative] Early in the history of calculus, many mathematicians assumed that a continuous function was differentiable at most points.
[src:calculus/derivative] Under mild conditions (for example, if the function is a monotone or a Lipschitz function), this is true.
[src:calculus/derivative] However, in 1872, Weierstrass found the first example of a function that is continuous everywhere but differentiable nowhere.
[src:calculus/derivative] This example is now known as the Weierstrass function.
[src:calculus/derivative] In 1931, Stefan Banach proved that the set of functions that have a derivative at some point is a meager set in the space of all continuous functions.
[src:calculus/derivative] Informally, this means that hardly any random continuous functions have a derivative at even one point.
[src:calculus/derivative] One common way of writing the derivative of a function is Leibniz notation, introduced by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1675, which denotes a derivative as the quotient of two differentials, such as $dy$ and ⁠ $dx$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] It is still commonly used when the equation $y=f(x)$ is viewed as a functional relationship between dependent and independent variables.
[src:calculus/derivative] The first derivative is denoted by ⁠ $\textstyle {\frac {dy}{dx}}$ ⁠, read as "the derivative of y with respect to ⁠ x ⁠".
[src:calculus/derivative] This derivative can alternately be treated as the application of a differential operator to a function, ${\textstyle {\frac {dy}{dx}}={\frac {d}{dx}}f(x).}$ Higher derivatives are expressed using the notation ${\textstyle {\frac {d^{n}y}{dx^{n}}}}$ for the n th derivative of ⁠ $y=f(x)$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] Another common notation for differentiation is by using the prime mark in the symbol of a function ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] This notation, due to Joseph-Louis Lagrange, is now known as *prime notation*.
[src:calculus/derivative] The first derivative is written as ⁠ $f'(x)$ ⁠, read as "⁠ f ⁠ prime of ⁠ x ⁠", or ⁠ $y'$ ⁠, read as "⁠ y ⁠ prime".
[src:calculus/derivative] Similarly, the second and the third derivatives can be written as $f''$ and ⁠ $f'''$ ⁠, respectively.
[src:calculus/derivative] For denoting the number of higher derivatives beyond this point, some authors use Roman numerals in superscript, whereas others place the number in parentheses, such as $f^{\mathrm {iv} }$ or ⁠ $f^{(4)}$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] The latter notation generalizes to yield the notation $f^{(n)}$ for the ⁠ n ⁠th derivative of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] In Newton's notation or the *dot notation,* a dot is placed over a symbol to represent a time derivative.
[src:calculus/derivative] If y is a function of ⁠ t ⁠, then the first and second derivatives can be written as ${\dot {y}}$ and ⁠ ${\ddot {y}}$ ⁠, respectively.
[src:calculus/derivative] This notation is used exclusively for derivatives with respect to time or arc length.
[src:calculus/derivative] It is typically used in differential equations in physics and differential geometry.
[src:calculus/derivative] However, the dot notation becomes unmanageable for high-order derivatives (of order 4 or more) and cannot deal with multiple independent variables.
[src:calculus/derivative] Another notation is *D-notation*, which represents the differential operator by the symbol ⁠ D ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] The first derivative is written $Df(x)$ and higher derivatives are written with a superscript, so the n th derivative is ⁠ $D^{n}f(x)$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] This notation is sometimes called *Euler notation*, although it seems that Leonhard Euler did not use it, and the notation was introduced by Louis François Antoine Arbogast.
[src:calculus/derivative] To indicate a partial derivative, the variable differentiated by is indicated with a subscript, for example given the function ⁠ $u=f(x,y)$ ⁠, its partial derivative with respect to x can be written $D_{x}u$ or ⁠ $D_{x}f(x,y)$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] In principle, the derivative of a function can be computed from the definition by considering the difference quotient and computing its limit.
[src:calculus/derivative] Once the derivatives of a few simple functions are known, the derivatives of functions obtained from these simple functions by applying elementary operations, such as products, sums, quotients, or function composition, to them can be determined by applying rules for differentiation.
[src:calculus/derivative] This process of finding a derivative is called **differentiation**.
[src:calculus/derivative] The following are the rules for the derivatives of the most common basic functions.
[src:calculus/derivative] Here, a is a real number, and e is the base of the natural logarithm, approximately 2.71828.
[src:calculus/derivative] The known derivatives of the elementary functions ⁠ $x^{2}$ ⁠, ⁠ $x^{4}$ ⁠, ⁠ $\sin(x)$ ⁠, ⁠ $\ln(x)$ ⁠, and ⁠ $\exp(x)$ ⁠, as well as the constant ⁠ 7 ⁠, were also used.
[src:calculus/derivative] An antiderivative of a function f is a function whose derivative is ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] Antiderivatives are not unique: if A is an antiderivative of ⁠ f ⁠, then so is ⁠ $A+c$ ⁠, where c is any constant, because the derivative of a constant is zero.
[src:calculus/derivative] The fundamental theorem of calculus shows that finding an antiderivative of a function gives a way to compute the areas of shapes bounded by that function.
[src:calculus/derivative] More precisely, the integral of a function over a closed interval is equal to the difference between the values of an antiderivative evaluated at the endpoints of that interval.
[src:calculus/derivative] One application of higher-order derivatives is in physics.
[src:calculus/derivative] For example, if the function ⁠ x ⁠ represents an object's position with respect to time, ⁠ $x'$ ⁠ represents the object's velocity, ⁠ $x''$ ⁠ represents the object's acceleration, and ⁠ $x'''$ ⁠ represents the object's jerk.
[src:calculus/derivative] A vector-valued function $\mathbf {y}$ of a real variable sends real numbers to vectors in some vector space ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] This includes, for example, parametric curves in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ or ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] The coordinate functions are real-valued functions, so the above definition of derivative applies to them.
[src:calculus/derivative] The derivative of $\mathbf {y} (t)$ is defined to be the vector, called the tangent vector, whose coordinates are the derivatives of the coordinate functions.
[src:calculus/derivative] The subtraction in the numerator is the subtraction of vectors, not scalars.
[src:calculus/derivative] If the derivative of $\mathbf {y}$ exists for every value of ⁠ t ⁠, then $\mathbf {y} '$ is another vector-valued function.
[src:calculus/derivative] Functions can depend upon more than one variable.
[src:calculus/derivative] A partial derivative of a function of several variables is its derivative with respect to one of those variables, with the others held constant.
[src:calculus/derivative] Partial derivatives are used in vector calculus and differential geometry.
[src:calculus/derivative] It can be thought of as the rate of change of the function in the x -direction.
[src:calculus/derivative] Here ∂ is a rounded *d* called the **partial derivative symbol**.
[src:calculus/derivative] To distinguish it from the letter *d*, ∂ is sometimes pronounced "der", "del", or "partial" instead of "dee".
[src:calculus/derivative] This is fundamental for the study of the functions of several real variables.
[src:calculus/derivative] Let $f(x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ be such a real-valued function.
[src:calculus/derivative] If f is differentiable at every point in some domain, then the gradient is a vector-valued function $\nabla f$ that maps the point $(a_{1},\dots ,a_{n})$ to the vector ⁠ $\nabla f(a_{1},\dots ,a_{n})$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] Consequently, the gradient determines a vector field.
[src:calculus/derivative] If f is a real-valued function on ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠, then the partial derivatives of f measure its variation in the direction of the coordinate axes.
[src:calculus/derivative] For example, if f is a function of x and ⁠ y ⁠, then its partial derivatives measure the variation in f in the x and y direction.
[src:calculus/derivative] However, they do not directly measure the variation of f in any other direction, such as along the diagonal line ⁠ $y=x$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] These are measured using directional derivatives.
[src:calculus/derivative] When f is a function from an open subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ ⁠, then the directional derivative of f in a chosen direction is the best linear approximation to f at that point and in that direction.
[src:calculus/derivative] However, when ⁠ $n>1$ ⁠, no single directional derivative can give a complete picture of the behavior of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] The total derivative gives a complete picture by considering all directions at once.
[src:calculus/derivative] However, $f'(\mathbf {a} )\mathbf {h}$ is a vector in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ ⁠, and the norm in the numerator is the standard length on ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] If v is a vector starting at ⁠ a ⁠, then $f'(\mathbf {a} )\mathbf {v}$ is called the pushforward of $\mathbf {v}$ by ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] If the total derivative exists at ⁠ $\mathbf {a}$ ⁠, then all the partial derivatives and directional derivatives of f exist at ⁠ $\mathbf {a}$ ⁠, and for all ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠, $f'(\mathbf {a} )\mathbf {v}$ is the directional derivative of f in the direction ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠.
[src:calculus/derivative] If f is written using coordinate functions, so that ⁠ $f=(f_{1},f_{2},\dots ,f_{m})$ ⁠, then the total derivative can be expressed using the partial derivatives as a matrix.
[src:calculus/derivative] The concept of a derivative can be extended to many other settings.
[src:calculus/derivative] The common thread is that the derivative of a function at a point serves as a linear approximation of the function at that point.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] In mathematics, a **differential equation** is an equation that relates one or more unknown functions and their derivatives.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Only the simplest differential equations are solvable by explicit formulas; however, many properties of solutions of a given differential equation may be determined without computing them exactly.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Often when a closed-form expression for the solutions is not available, solutions may be approximated numerically using computers, and many numerical methods have been developed to determine solutions with a given degree of accuracy.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The theory of dynamical systems analyzes the qualitative aspects of solutions, such as their average behavior over a long time interval.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Differential equations came into existence with the invention of calculus by Isaac Newton and Gottfried Leibniz.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] In all these cases, y is an unknown function of x (or of *x*1 and *x*2), and f is a given function.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] He solved these examples and others using infinite series and discussed the non-uniqueness of solutions.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Jacob Bernoulli proposed the Bernoulli differential equation in 1695.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] for which the following year Leibniz obtained solutions by simplifying it.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Historically, the problem of a vibrating string such as that of a musical instrument was studied by Jean le Rond d'Alembert, Leonhard Euler, Daniel Bernoulli, and Joseph-Louis Lagrange.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] In 1746, d’Alembert discovered the one-dimensional wave equation, and within ten years Euler discovered the three-dimensional wave equation.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The Euler–Lagrange equation was developed in the 1750s by Euler and Lagrange in connection with their studies of the tautochrone problem.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] This is the problem of determining a curve on which a weighted particle will fall to a fixed point in a fixed amount of time, independent of the starting point.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Lagrange solved this problem in 1755 and sent the solution to Euler.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Both further developed Lagrange's method and applied it to mechanics, which led to the formulation of Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Contained in this book was Fourier's proposal of his heat equation for conductive diffusion of heat.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] This partial differential equation is now a common part of mathematical physics curriculum.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] In classical mechanics, the motion of a body is described by its position and velocity as the time value varies.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Newton's laws allow these variables to be expressed dynamically (given the position, velocity, and various forces acting on the body) as a differential equation for the unknown position of the body as a function of time.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] In some cases, this differential equation (called an equation of motion) may be solved explicitly.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] An example of modeling a real-world problem using differential equations is the determination of the velocity of a ball falling through the air, considering only gravity and air resistance.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The ball's acceleration towards the ground is the acceleration due to gravity minus the deceleration due to air resistance.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Gravity is considered constant, and air resistance may be modeled as proportional to the ball's velocity.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] This means that the ball's acceleration, which is a derivative of its velocity, depends on the velocity (and the velocity depends on time).
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Finding the velocity as a function of time involves solving a differential equation and verifying its validity.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Differential equations can be classified several different ways.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Besides describing the properties of the equation itself, these classes of differential equations can help inform the choice of approach to a solution.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Commonly used distinctions include whether the equation is ordinary or partial, linear or non-linear, and homogeneous or heterogeneous.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] This list is far from exhaustive; there are many other properties and subclasses of differential equations which can be very useful in specific contexts.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] An ordinary differential equation (*ODE*) is an equation containing an unknown function of one real or complex variable x, its derivatives, and some given functions of x.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The unknown function is generally represented by a dependent variable (often denoted y), which, therefore, *depends* on x.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Thus x is often called the independent variable of the equation.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The term "*ordinary*" is used in contrast with the term partial differential equation, which may be with respect to *more than* one independent variable.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] As, in general, the solutions of a differential equation cannot be expressed by a closed-form expression, numerical methods are commonly used for solving differential equations on a computer.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] A partial differential equation (*PDE*) is a differential equation that contains unknown multivariable functions and their partial derivatives.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] PDEs are used to formulate problems involving functions of several variables, and are either solved in closed form, or using a relevant computer model.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] PDEs can be used to describe a wide variety of phenomena in nature such as sound, heat, electrostatics, electrodynamics, fluid flow, elasticity, or quantum mechanics.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] These seemingly distinct physical phenomena can be formalized similarly in terms of PDEs.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Just as ordinary differential equations often model one-dimensional dynamical systems, partial differential equations often model multidimensional systems.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Stochastic partial differential equations generalize partial differential equations for modeling randomness.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Linear differential equations are differential equations that are linear in the unknown function and its derivatives.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Their theory is well developed, and in many cases one may express their solutions in terms of integrals.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Many differential equations that are encountered in physics are linear, for example ODEs describing radioactive decay and PDEs for heat transfer by thermal diffusion.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] These lead to special functions, which may be defined as solutions of linear differential equations (see Holonomic function).
[src:calculus/differential-equation] A **non-linear differential equation** is a differential equation that is not a linear equation in the unknown function and its derivatives (the linearity or non-linearity in the arguments of the function are not considered here).
[src:calculus/differential-equation] There are very few methods of solving nonlinear differential equations exactly; those that are known typically depend on the equation having particular symmetries.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Nonlinear differential equations can exhibit very complicated behaviour over extended time intervals, characteristic of chaos.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Even the fundamental questions of existence and uniqueness of solutions for nonlinear differential equations are hard problems and their resolution in special cases is considered to be a significant advance in the mathematical theory (cf.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Navier–Stokes existence and smoothness).
[src:calculus/differential-equation] However, if the differential equation is a correctly formulated representation of a meaningful physical process, then one expects it to have a solution.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] In some circumstances, nonlinear differential equations may be approximated by linear ones.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] These approximations are only valid under restricted conditions.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] For example, the harmonic oscillator equation is an approximation to the nonlinear pendulum equation that is valid for small amplitude oscillations.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Similarly, when a fixed point or stationary solution of a nonlinear differential equation has been found, investigation of its stability leads to a linear differential equation.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The **order of the differential equation** is the highest *order of derivative* of the unknown function that appears in the differential equation.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] For example, an equation containing only first-order derivatives is a *first-order differential equation*, an equation containing the second-order derivative is a *second-order differential equation*, and so on.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] When it is written as a polynomial equation in the unknown function and its derivatives, the **degree of the differential equation** is, depending on the context, the polynomial degree in the highest derivative of the unknown function, or its total degree in the unknown function and its derivatives.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] In particular, a linear differential equation has degree one for both meanings, but the non-linear differential equation $y'+y^{2}=0$ is of degree one for the first meaning but not for the second one.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Differential equations that describe natural phenomena usually have only first and second order derivatives in them, but there are some exceptions, such as the thin-film equation, which is a fourth order partial differential equation.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] A linear differential equation is *homogeneous* if each term in the equation includes either the dependent variable or one of its derivatives.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] If this is not the case, so that there is a term that does not include either the dependent variable itself or a derivative of it, the equation is *inhomogeneous* or *heterogeneous*.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The first group of examples are ordinary differential equations, where *u* is an unknown function of *x*, and *c* and *ω* are constants that are assumed to be known.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] These examples illustrate the distinction between *linear* and *nonlinear* differential equations, and between homogeneous differential equations and *inhomogeneous* ones, defined above.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The next group of examples are partial differential equations.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The unknown function *u* depends on two variables *x* and *t* or *x* and *y*.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The general solution of a first-order ordinary differential equation includes a constant, which can be thought of as a constant of integration.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Similarly, the general solution of a n th order ODE contains n constants.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] To determine the values of these constants, additional conditions must be provided.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] If the independent variable corresponds to time, this information takes the form of initial conditions.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] For example, for a second-order ODE describing the motion of a particle, the initial conditions would typically be the position and velocity of the particle at the initial time.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The ODE and its initial conditions form what is known as an initial value problem.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] For the case of a spatial independent variable, these conditions are generally known as boundary conditions.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] These are often specified at different values of the independent variable.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Examples include the motion of a vibrating string that is fixed at two endpoints.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] In this case the ODE and boundary conditions lead to a boundary value problem.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] More generally, the term *initial conditions* is normally used when the conditions are given at the same value of the independent variable, and the term *boundary conditions* is used when they are specified at different values of the independent variable.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] In either case, the number of initial or boundary conditions should match the order of the differential equation.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] For a given differential equation, the questions of whether solutions are unique or exist at all are notable subjects of interest.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] For a first-order initial value problem, the Peano existence theorem gives one set of circumstances in which a solution exists.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Given any point $(a,b)$ in the xy-plane, define some rectangular region Z , such that $Z=[l,m]\times [n,p]$ and $(a,b)$ is in the interior of Z .
[src:calculus/differential-equation] If we are given a differential equation ${\textstyle {\frac {dy}{dx}}=g(x,y)}$ and the condition that $y=b$ when $x=a$ , then there is locally a solution to this problem if $g(x,y)$ is continuous on Z .
[src:calculus/differential-equation] This solution exists on some interval with its center at a .
[src:calculus/differential-equation] However, this only helps us with first order initial value problems.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] For any nonzero $f_{n}(x)$ , if $\{f_{0},f_{1},\ldots \}$ and g are continuous on some interval containing $x_{0}$ , y exists and is unique.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Differential equations are closely related to difference equations, in which the independent variable assumes only discrete values, and the equation relates the value of the unknown function at a point to its values at nearby points.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Many numerical methods for differential equations, for example the Euler method, involve the approximation of the solution of a differential equation by the solution of a corresponding difference equation.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The study of differential equations is a wide field in pure and applied mathematics, physics, and engineering.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] All of these disciplines are concerned with the properties of differential equations of various types.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Pure mathematics focuses on the existence and uniqueness of solutions, while applied mathematics is concerned with finding solutions, either directly or approximately, and studying their behaviour.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Differential equations play an important role in modeling virtually every physical, technical, or biological process, from celestial motion, to bridge design, to interactions between neurons.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Differential equations such as those used to solve real-life problems may not have closed form solutions.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Instead, solutions can be approximated using numerical methods.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Many fundamental laws of physics and chemistry can be formulated as differential equations.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] In biology and economics, differential equations are used to model the behavior of complex systems.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The mathematical theory of differential equations first developed together with the sciences where the equations had originated and where the results found application.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] However, diverse problems, sometimes originating in quite distinct scientific fields, may give rise to identical differential equations.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] When this happens, mathematical theory behind the equations can be viewed as a unifying principle behind diverse phenomena.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] As an example, consider the propagation of light and sound in the atmosphere, and of waves on the surface of a pond.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] All of them may be described by the same second-order partial differential equation, the wave equation, which allows us to think of light and sound as forms of waves, much like familiar waves in the water.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Conduction of heat, the theory of which was developed by Joseph Fourier, is governed by another second-order partial differential equation, the heat equation.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] It turns out that many diffusion processes, while seemingly different, are described by the same equation.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] The number of differential equations that have received a name, in various scientific areas, demonstrates the importance of the topic.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] See List of named differential equations.
[src:calculus/differential-equation] Some CAS software can solve differential equations.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Roughly speaking, the two operations can be thought of as inverses of each other.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The first part of the theorem, the **first fundamental theorem of calculus**, states that for a continuous function f , an antiderivative or indefinite integral F can be obtained as the integral of f over an interval with a variable upper bound.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Conversely, the second part of the theorem, the **second fundamental theorem of calculus**, states that the integral of a function f over a fixed interval is equal to the change of any antiderivative F between the ends of the interval.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] This greatly simplifies the calculation of a definite integral provided an antiderivative can be found by symbolic integration, thus avoiding numerical integration.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The fundamental theorem of calculus relates differentiation and integration, showing that these two operations are essentially inverses of one another.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Before the discovery of this theorem, it was not recognized that these two operations were related.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Ancient Greek mathematicians knew how to compute area via infinitesimals, an operation that we would now call integration.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The origins of differentiation likewise predate the fundamental theorem of calculus by hundreds of years; for example, in the fourteenth century the notions of *continuity* of functions and *motion* were studied by the Oxford Calculators and other scholars.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The historical relevance of the fundamental theorem of calculus is not the ability to calculate these operations, but the realization that the two seemingly distinct operations (calculation of geometric areas, and calculation of gradients) are actually closely related.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Calculus as a unified theory of integration and differentiation started from the conjecture and the proof of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The first published statement and proof of a rudimentary form of the fundamental theorem, strongly geometric in character, was by James Gregory (1638–1675).
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Isaac Barrow (1630–1677) proved a more generalized version of the theorem, while his student Isaac Newton (1642–1727) completed the development of the surrounding mathematical theory.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Gottfried Leibniz (1646–1716) systematized the knowledge into a calculus for infinitesimal quantities and introduced the notation used today.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The first fundamental theorem may be interpreted as follows.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Given a continuous function $y=f(x)$ whose graph is plotted as a curve, one defines a corresponding "area function" $x\mapsto A(x)$ such that *A*(*x*) is the area beneath the curve between 0 and x.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The area *A*(*x*) may not be easily computable, but it is assumed to be well defined.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The area under the curve between x and *x* + *h* could be computed by finding the area between 0 and *x* + *h*, then subtracting the area between 0 and x.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] In other words, the area of this "strip" would be *A*(*x* + *h*) − *A*(*x*).
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] There is another way to *estimate* the area of this same strip.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] As shown in the accompanying figure, h is multiplied by *f*(*x*) to find the area of a rectangle that is approximately the same size as this strip.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Thus, the derivative of the integral of a function (the area) is the original function, so that derivative and integral are inverse operations which reverse each other.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] This is the essence of the Fundamental Theorem.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Intuitively, the fundamental theorem states that *integration* and *differentiation* are inverse operations which reverse each other.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The second fundamental theorem says that the sum of infinitesimal changes in a quantity (the integral of the derivative of the quantity) adds up to the net change in the quantity.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] To visualize this, imagine traveling in a car and wanting to know the distance traveled (the net change in position along the highway).
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] You can see the velocity on the speedometer but cannot look out to see your location.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Each second, you can find how far the car has traveled using distance = speed × time, that is, multiplying the current speed (in kilometers or miles per hour) by the time interval (1 second = ${\tfrac {1}{3600}}$ hour).
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Thus, the integral of the velocity function (the derivative of position) computes how far the car has traveled (the net change in position).
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The first fundamental theorem says that the value of any function is the rate of change (the derivative) of its integral from a fixed starting point up to any chosen end point.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Continuing the above example using a velocity as the function, you can integrate it from the starting time up to any given time to obtain a distance function whose derivative is that velocity.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The first part deals with the derivative of an antiderivative, while the second part deals with the relationship between antiderivatives and definite integrals.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The terminology on this topic has not been completely standardized.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] For convenience, this article uses one of the common conventions.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The conventions adopted in other sources are discussed later.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] This part is sometimes referred to as the *first fundamental theorem of calculus*.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Let f be a continuous real-valued function defined on a closed interval [*a*, *b*].
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Then F is uniformly continuous on [*a*, *b*] and differentiable on the open interval (*a*, *b*), and $F'(x)=f(x)$ for all x in (*a*, *b*) so F is an antiderivative of f.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The fundamental theorem is often employed to compute the definite integral of a function f for which an antiderivative F is known.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The corollary assumes continuity on the whole interval.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] This result is strengthened slightly in the following part of the theorem.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] This part is sometimes referred to as the *second fundamental theorem of calculus* or the **Newton–Leibniz theorem**.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The second part is somewhat stronger than the corollary because it does not assume that f is continuous.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] When an antiderivative F of f exists, then there are infinitely many antiderivatives for f , obtained by adding an arbitrary constant to F .
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Also, by the first part of the theorem, antiderivatives of f always exist when f is continuous.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Suppose F is an antiderivative of f, with f continuous on [*a*, *b*].
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] By the *first part* of the theorem, we know G is also an antiderivative of f.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Since *F*′ − *G*′ = 0 the mean value theorem implies that *F* − *G* is a constant function, that is, there is a number c such that *G*(*x*) = *F*(*x*) + *c* for all x in [*a*, *b*].
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] To begin, we recall the mean value theorem.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Let f be (Riemann) integrable on the interval [*a*, *b*], and let f admit an antiderivative F on (*a*, *b*) such that F is continuous on [*a*, *b*].
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The function F is differentiable on the interval (*a*, *b*) and continuous on the closed interval [*a*, *b*]; therefore, it is also differentiable on each interval (*x**i*−1, *x**i*) and continuous on each interval [*x**i*−1, *x**i*].
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The assumption implies $F'(c_{i})=f(c_{i}).$ Also, $x_{i}-x_{i-1}$ can be expressed as $\Delta x$ of partition i .
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] We are describing the area of a rectangle, with the width times the height, and we are adding the areas together.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Each rectangle, by virtue of the mean value theorem, describes an approximation of the curve section it is drawn over.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Also $\Delta x_{i}$ need not be the same for all values of i, or in other words that the width of the rectangles can differ.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] What we have to do is approximate the curve with n rectangles.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Now, as the size of the partitions get smaller and n increases, resulting in more partitions to cover the space, we get closer and closer to the actual area of the curve.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] By taking the limit of the expression as the norm of the partitions approaches zero, we arrive at the Riemann integral.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] We know that this limit exists because f was assumed to be integrable.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] That is, we take the limit as the largest of the partitions approaches zero in size, so that all other partitions are smaller and the number of partitions approaches infinity.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] So, we take the limit on both sides of (**2'**).
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The expression on the right side of the equation defines the integral over f from a to b.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Therefore, we obtain $F(b)-F(a)=\int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx,$ which completes the proof.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] As discussed above, a slightly weaker version of the second part follows from the first part.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Similarly, it almost looks like the first part of the theorem follows directly from the second.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] That is, suppose G is an antiderivative of f.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Then F has the same derivative as G, and therefore *F*′ = *f*.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] This argument only works, however, if we already know that f has an antiderivative, and the only way we know that all continuous functions have antiderivatives is by the first part of the Fundamental Theorem.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] For example, if *f*(*x*) = *e*−*x*2, then f has an antiderivative, namely $G(x)=\int _{0}^{x}f(t)\,dt$ and there is no simpler expression for this function.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] It is therefore important not to interpret the second part of the theorem as the definition of the integral.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Indeed, there are many functions that are integrable but lack elementary antiderivatives, and discontinuous functions can be integrable but lack any antiderivatives at all.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Conversely, many functions that have antiderivatives are not Riemann integrable (see Volterra's function).
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] This can also be checked using the second part of the theorem.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Moreover, this is not just a matter of how f is defined at zero, since the limit as $x\to 0$ of $f(x)$ does not exist.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Apostol's calculus series uses this terminology, and similarly, Strang et al. call this "part 1" of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Multiple other texts also call this result the first fundamental theorem or the fundamental theorem's first part.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] On the other hand, Larson and Edwards adopt a different convention, in which "the fundamental theorem" is that the definite integral is the change of the antiderivative, $F(x)-F(c)=\int _{c}^{x}f(t)\,dt\,$ for a continuous function f .
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] That is, this article's "corollary" is designated "the fundamental theorem", while the "second fundamental theorem" is what Apostol calls the first.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Other textbooks also call this article's "second fundamental theorem", or a weaker form of it that assumes continuity, the first.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Salas and Hille's *Calculus: One and Several Variables* (1971) says that the latter expression in the special case of continuous f (this article's "corollary") is "the fundamental theorem of integral calculus", while this article's "first part" is just the un-named Theorem 4.3.2.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Similarly, some other works call this article's "second part" *the* fundamental theorem while leaving the other part un-named.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Boyer's *History of the Calculus* first explains "what is commonly known as the fundamental theorem of the calculus": that if $F(x)=\int _{a}^{x}f(t)\,dt$ , then $F'(x)=f(x)$ .
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] For Boyer, our "first part" is "the fundamental theorem".
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Then, Boyer writes that the difference of the antiderivatives $F(b)-F(a)$ "is occasionally taken as the definition" of the integral $\int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx$ .
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The function f does not have to be continuous over the whole interval.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] We can relax the conditions on f still further and suppose that it is merely locally integrable.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] In that case, we can conclude that the function F is differentiable almost everywhere and *F*′(*x*) = *f*(*x*) almost everywhere.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] On the real line this statement is equivalent to Lebesgue's differentiation theorem.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] These results remain true for the Henstock–Kurzweil integral, which allows a larger class of integrable functions.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] In higher dimensions Lebesgue's differentiation theorem generalizes the Fundamental theorem of calculus by stating that for almost every x, the average value of a function f over a ball of radius r centered at x tends to *f*(*x*) as r tends to 0.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Part II of the theorem is true for any Lebesgue integrable function f, which has an antiderivative F (not all integrable functions do, though).
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] This result may fail for continuous functions F that admit a derivative *f*(*x*) at almost every point x, as the example of the Cantor function shows.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] However, if F is absolutely continuous, it admits a derivative *F′*(*x*) at almost every point x, and moreover F′ is integrable, with *F*(*b*) − *F*(*a*) equal to the integral of F′ on [*a*, *b*].
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Conversely, if f is any integrable function, then F as given in the first formula will be absolutely continuous with *F′* = *f* almost everywhere.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The conditions of this theorem may again be relaxed by considering the integrals involved as Henstock–Kurzweil integrals.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Specifically, if a continuous function *F*(*x*) admits a derivative *f*(*x*) at all but countably many points, then *f*(*x*) is Henstock–Kurzweil integrable and *F*(*b*) − *F*(*a*) is equal to the integral of f on [*a*, *b*].
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The difference here is that the integrability of f does not need to be assumed.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The version of Taylor's theorem that expresses the error term as an integral can be seen as a generalization of the fundamental theorem.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] There is a version of the theorem for complex functions: suppose U is an open set in **C** and *f* : *U* → **C** is a function that has a holomorphic antiderivative F on U.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The fundamental theorem can be generalized to curve and surface integrals in higher dimensions and on manifolds.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] One such generalization offered by the calculus of moving surfaces is the time evolution of integrals.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The most familiar extensions of the fundamental theorem of calculus in higher dimensions are the divergence theorem and the gradient theorem.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] One of the most powerful generalizations in this direction is the generalized Stokes theorem (sometimes known as the fundamental theorem of multivariable calculus): Let M be an oriented piecewise smooth manifold of dimension n and let $\omega$ be a smooth compactly supported (*n* − 1)-form on M.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] Here *d* is the exterior derivative, which is defined using the manifold structure only.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The theorem is often used in situations where M is an embedded oriented submanifold of some bigger manifold (e.g.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] **R***k*) on which the form $\omega$ is defined.
[src:calculus/fundamental-theorem-of-calculus] The fundamental theorem of calculus allows us to pose a definite integral as a first-order ordinary differential equation. $\int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx$ can be posed as ${\frac {dy}{dx}}=f(x),\;\;y(a)=0$ with $y(b)$ as the value of the integral.
[src:calculus/gradient] In vector calculus, the **gradient** of a scalar-valued differentiable function f of several variables is the vector field (or vector-valued function) $\nabla f$ whose value at a point p gives the direction and the rate of fastest increase.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient transforms like a vector under change of basis of the space of variables of f .
[src:calculus/gradient] If the gradient of a function is non-zero at a point p , the direction of the gradient is the direction in which the function increases most quickly from p , and the magnitude of the gradient is the rate of increase in that direction, the greatest absolute directional derivative.
[src:calculus/gradient] Further, a point where the gradient is the zero vector is known as a stationary point.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient thus plays a fundamental role in optimization theory, machine learning, and artificial intelligence, where it is used to minimize a function by gradient descent.
[src:calculus/gradient] where $df$ is the total infinitesimal change in f for an infinitesimal displacement $d\mathbf {r}$ , and is seen to be maximal when $d\mathbf {r}$ is in the direction of the gradient $\nabla f$ .
[src:calculus/gradient] The nabla symbol $\nabla$ , written as an upside-down triangle and pronounced "del", denotes the vector differential operator.
[src:calculus/gradient] When a coordinate system is used in which the basis vectors are not functions of position, the gradient is given by the vector whose components are the partial derivatives of f at p .
[src:calculus/gradient] Note that the above definition for gradient is defined for the function f only if f is differentiable at p .
[src:calculus/gradient] There can be functions for which partial derivatives exist in every direction but fail to be differentiable.
[src:calculus/gradient] Furthermore, this definition as the vector of partial derivatives is only valid when the basis of the coordinate system is orthonormal.
[src:calculus/gradient] For any other basis, the metric tensor at that point needs to be taken into account.
[src:calculus/gradient] For example, the function $f(x,y)={\frac {x^{2}y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}}$ unless at origin where $f(0,0)=0$ , is not differentiable at the origin as it does not have a well defined tangent plane despite having well defined partial derivatives in every direction at the origin.
[src:calculus/gradient] In this particular example, under rotation of x-y coordinate system, the above formula for gradient fails to transform like a vector (gradient becomes dependent on choice of basis for coordinate system) and also fails to point towards the 'steepest ascent' in some orientations.
[src:calculus/gradient] For differentiable functions where the formula for gradient holds, it can be shown to always transform as a vector under transformation of the basis so as to always point towards the fastest increase.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient is dual to the total derivative $df$ : the value of the gradient at a point is a tangent vector – a vector at each point; while the value of the derivative at a point is a *co*tangent vector – a linear functional on vectors.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient admits multiple generalizations to more general functions on manifolds; see § Generalizations.
[src:calculus/gradient] Consider a room where the temperature is given by a scalar field, *T*, so at each point (*x*, *y*, *z*) the temperature is *T*(*x*, *y*, *z*), independent of time.
[src:calculus/gradient] At each point in the room, the gradient of *T* at that point will show the direction in which the temperature rises most quickly, moving away from (*x*, *y*, *z*).
[src:calculus/gradient] The magnitude of the gradient will determine how fast the temperature rises in that direction.
[src:calculus/gradient] Consider a surface whose height above sea level at point (*x*, *y*) is *H*(*x*, *y*).
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient of *H* at a point is a plane vector pointing in the direction of the steepest slope or grade at that point.
[src:calculus/gradient] The steepness of the slope at that point is given by the magnitude of the gradient vector.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient can also be used to measure how a scalar field changes in other directions, rather than just the direction of greatest change, by taking a dot product.
[src:calculus/gradient] Suppose that the steepest slope on a hill is 40%.
[src:calculus/gradient] A road going directly uphill has slope 40%, but a road going around the hill at an angle will have a shallower slope.
[src:calculus/gradient] More generally, if the hill height function *H* is differentiable, then the gradient of *H* dotted with a unit vector gives the slope of the hill in the direction of the vector, the directional derivative of *H* along the unit vector.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient of a function f at point a is usually written as $\nabla f(a)$ .
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient (or gradient vector field) of a scalar function *f*(*x*1, *x*2, *x*3, …, *xn*) is denoted ∇*f* or ∇→*f* where ∇ (nabla) denotes the vector differential operator, del.
[src:calculus/gradient] The notation grad *f* is also commonly used to represent the gradient.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient of *f* is defined as the unique vector field whose dot product with any vector **v** at each point *x* is the directional derivative of *f* along **v**.
[src:calculus/gradient] where the right-hand side is the directional derivative and there are many ways to represent it.
[src:calculus/gradient] Formally, the derivative is *dual* to the gradient; see relationship with derivative.
[src:calculus/gradient] When a function also depends on a parameter such as time, the gradient often refers simply to the vector of its spatial derivatives only (see Spatial gradient).
[src:calculus/gradient] The magnitude and direction of the gradient vector are independent of the particular coordinate representation.
[src:calculus/gradient] where **i**, **j**, **k** are the standard unit vectors in the directions of the *x*, *y* and *z* coordinates, respectively.
[src:calculus/gradient] In some applications it is customary to represent the gradient as a row vector or column vector of its components in a rectangular coordinate system; this article follows the convention of the gradient being a column vector, while the derivative is a row vector.
[src:calculus/gradient] where *ρ* is the axial distance, *φ* is the azimuthal or azimuth angle, *z* is the axial coordinate, and **e***ρ*, **e***φ* and **e***z* are unit vectors pointing along the coordinate directions.
[src:calculus/gradient] where *r* is the radial distance, *φ* is the azimuthal angle and *θ* is the polar angle, and **e***r*, **e***θ* and **e***φ* are again local unit vectors pointing in the coordinate directions (that is, the normalized covariant basis).
[src:calculus/gradient] For the gradient in other orthogonal coordinate systems, see Orthogonal coordinates (Differential operators in three dimensions).
[src:calculus/gradient] We consider general coordinates, which we write as *x*1, …, *x**i*, …, *x**n*, where n is the number of dimensions of the domain.
[src:calculus/gradient] Here, the upper index refers to the position in the list of the coordinate or component, so *x*2 refers to the second component—not the quantity *x* squared.
[src:calculus/gradient] The index variable *i* refers to an arbitrary element *x**i*.
[src:calculus/gradient] where $\mathbf {e} ^{i}=\mathrm {d} x^{i}$ and $\mathbf {e} _{i}=\partial \mathbf {x} /\partial x^{i}$ refer to the unnormalized local covariant and contravariant bases respectively, $g^{ij}$ is the inverse metric tensor, and the Einstein summation convention implies summation over *i* and *j*.
[src:calculus/gradient] where we cannot use Einstein notation, since it is impossible to avoid the repetition of more than two indices.
[src:calculus/gradient] Despite the use of upper and lower indices, $\mathbf {\hat {e}} _{i}$ , $\mathbf {\hat {e}} ^{i}$ , and $h_{i}$ are neither contravariant nor covariant.
[src:calculus/gradient] The latter expression evaluates to the expressions given above for cylindrical and spherical coordinates.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient is closely related to the total derivative (total differential) $df$ : they are transpose (dual) to each other.
[src:calculus/gradient] In symbols, the gradient is an element of the tangent space at a point, $\nabla f(p)\in T_{p}\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , while the derivative is a map from the tangent space to the real numbers, $df_{p}\colon T_{p}\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:calculus/gradient] The best linear approximation to a differentiable function $f:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ at a point x in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is a linear map from $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to $\mathbb {R}$ which is often denoted by $df_{x}$ or $Df(x)$ and called the differential or total derivative of f at x .
[src:calculus/gradient] The function $df$ , which maps x to $df_{x}$ , is called the total differential or exterior derivative of f and is an example of a differential 1-form.
[src:calculus/gradient] Much as the derivative of a function of a single variable represents the slope of the tangent to the graph of the function, the directional derivative of a function in several variables represents the slope of the tangent hyperplane in the direction of the vector.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient is related to the differential by the formula $(\nabla f)_{x}\cdot v=df_{x}(v)$ for any $v\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , where $\cdot$ is the dot product: taking the dot product of a vector with the gradient is the same as taking the directional derivative along the vector.
[src:calculus/gradient] The best linear approximation to a function can be expressed in terms of the gradient, rather than the derivative.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient of a function f from the Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to $\mathbb {R}$ at any particular point $x_{0}$ in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ characterizes the best linear approximation to f at $x_{0}$ .
[src:calculus/gradient] for x close to $x_{0}$ , where $(\nabla f)_{x_{0}}$ is the gradient of f computed at $x_{0}$ , and the dot denotes the dot product on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:calculus/gradient] This equation is equivalent to the first two terms in the multivariable Taylor series expansion of f at $x_{0}$ .
[src:calculus/gradient] If the function *f* : *U* → **R** is differentiable, then the differential of *f* is the Fréchet derivative of *f*.
[src:calculus/gradient] There are two forms of the chain rule applying to the gradient.
[src:calculus/gradient] More generally, if instead *I* ⊂ **R***k*, then the following holds: $\nabla (f\circ g)(c)={\big (}Dg(c){\big )}^{\mathsf {T}}{\big (}\nabla f(a){\big )},$ where (*Dg*)T denotes the transpose Jacobian matrix.
[src:calculus/gradient] For the second form of the chain rule, suppose that *h* : *I* → **R** is a real valued function on a subset *I* of **R**, and that *h* is differentiable at the point *f*(*a*) ∈ *I*.
[src:calculus/gradient] A level surface, or isosurface, is the set of all points where some function has a given value.
[src:calculus/gradient] If *f* is differentiable, then the dot product (∇*f* )*x* ⋅ *v* of the gradient at a point *x* with a vector *v* gives the directional derivative of *f* at *x* in the direction *v*.
[src:calculus/gradient] It follows that in this case the gradient of *f* is orthogonal to the level sets of *f*.
[src:calculus/gradient] For example, a level surface in three-dimensional space is defined by an equation of the form *F*(*x*, *y*, *z*) = *c*.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient of *F* is then normal to the surface.
[src:calculus/gradient] More generally, any embedded hypersurface in a Riemannian manifold can be cut out by an equation of the form *F*(*P*) = 0 such that *dF* is nowhere zero.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient of *F* is then normal to the hypersurface.
[src:calculus/gradient] Similarly, an affine algebraic hypersurface may be defined by an equation *F*(*x*1, ..., *x**n*) = 0, where *F* is a polynomial.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient of *F* is zero at a singular point of the hypersurface (this is the definition of a singular point).
[src:calculus/gradient] At a non-singular point, it is a nonzero normal vector.
[src:calculus/gradient] The gradient of a function is called a gradient field.
[src:calculus/gradient] A (continuous) gradient field is always a conservative vector field: its line integral along any path depends only on the endpoints of the path, and can be evaluated by the gradient theorem (the fundamental theorem of calculus for line integrals).
[src:calculus/gradient] Conversely, a (continuous) conservative vector field is always the gradient of a function.
[src:calculus/gradient] Let $v\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ be an arbitrary unit vector.
[src:calculus/gradient] where R denotes higher order terms in $vh$ .
[src:calculus/gradient] The Jacobian matrix is the generalization of the gradient for vector-valued functions of several variables and differentiable maps between Euclidean spaces or, more generally, manifolds.
[src:calculus/gradient] A further generalization for a function between Banach spaces is the Fréchet derivative.
[src:calculus/gradient] Suppose **f** : **R***n* → **R***m* is a function such that each of its first-order partial derivatives exist on ℝ*n*.
[src:calculus/gradient] Then the Jacobian matrix of **f** is defined to be an *m*×*n* matrix, denoted by $\mathbf {J} _{\mathbb {f} }(\mathbb {x} )$ or simply $\mathbf {J}$ .
[src:calculus/gradient] Since the total derivative of a vector field is a linear mapping from vectors to vectors, it is a tensor quantity.
[src:calculus/gradient] (where the Einstein summation notation is used and the tensor product of the vectors **e***i* and **e***k* is a dyadic tensor of type (2,0)).
[src:calculus/gradient] where *g**jk* are the components of the inverse metric tensor and the **e***i* are the coordinate basis vectors.
[src:calculus/gradient] The relation between the exterior derivative and the gradient of a function on **R***n* is a special case of this in which the metric is the flat metric given by the dot product.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In mathematics, an **integral** is the continuous analog of a sum, and is used to calculate areas, volumes, and their generalizations.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The process of computing an integral, called **integration**, is one of the two fundamental operations of calculus, along with differentiation.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Integration was initially used to solve problems in mathematics and physics, such as finding the **area under a curve**, or determining displacement from velocity.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Usage of integration expanded to a wide variety of scientific fields thereafter.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] A **definite integral** computes the signed area of the region in the plane that is bounded by the graph of a given function between two points in the real line.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Conventionally, areas above the horizontal axis of the plane are positive while areas below are negative.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Integrals also refer to the concept of an *antiderivative*, a function whose derivative is the given function; in this case, they are also called *indefinite integrals*.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The fundamental theorem of calculus relates definite integration to differentiation and provides a method to compute the definite integral of a function when its antiderivative is known; differentiation and integration are inverse operations.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Bernhard Riemann later gave a rigorous definition of integrals, which is based on a limiting procedure that approximates the area of a curvilinear region by breaking the region into infinitesimally thin vertical slabs.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In the early 20th century, Henri Lebesgue generalized Riemann's formulation by introducing what is now referred to as the Lebesgue integral; it is more general than Riemann's in the sense that a wider class of functions are Lebesgue-integrable.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Integrals may be generalized depending on the type of the function as well as the domain over which the integration is performed.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] For example, a line integral is defined for functions of two or more variables, and the interval of integration is replaced by a curve connecting two points in space.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In a surface integral, the curve is replaced by a piece of a surface in three-dimensional space.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] A similar method was independently developed in China around the 3rd century AD by Liu Hui, who used it to find the area of the circle.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] This method was later used in the 5th century by Chinese father-and-son mathematicians Zu Chongzhi and Zu Geng to find the volume of a sphere.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The next significant advances in integral calculus did not begin to appear until the 17th century.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] At this time, the work of Cavalieri with his method of indivisibles, and work by Fermat, began to lay the foundations of modern calculus, with Cavalieri computing the integrals of *x**n* up to degree *n* = 9 in Cavalieri's quadrature formula.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The case *n* = −1 required the invention of a function, the hyperbolic logarithm, achieved by quadrature of the hyperbola in 1647.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Further steps were made in the early 17th century by Barrow and Torricelli, who provided the first hints of a connection between integration and differentiation.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Barrow provided the first proof of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Wallis generalized Cavalieri's method, computing integrals of x to a general power, including negative powers and fractional powers.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The major advance in integration came in the 17th century with the independent discovery of the fundamental theorem of calculus by Leibniz and Newton.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The theorem demonstrates a connection between integration and differentiation.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] This connection, combined with the comparative ease of differentiation, can be exploited to calculate integrals.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In particular, the fundamental theorem of calculus allows one to solve a much broader class of problems.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Equal in importance is the comprehensive mathematical framework that both Leibniz and Newton developed.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Given the name infinitesimal calculus, it allowed for precise analysis of functions with continuous domains.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] This framework eventually became modern calculus, whose notation for integrals is drawn directly from the work of Leibniz.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] While Newton and Leibniz provided a systematic approach to integration, their work lacked a degree of rigour.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Bishop Berkeley memorably attacked the vanishing increments used by Newton, calling them "ghosts of departed quantities".
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Calculus acquired a firmer footing with the development of limits.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Integration was first rigorously formalized, using limits, by Riemann.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Other definitions of integral, extending Riemann's and Lebesgue's approaches, were proposed.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] These approaches based on the real number system are the ones most common today, but alternative approaches exist, such as a definition of integral as the standard part of an infinite Riemann sum, based on the hyperreal number system.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The notation for the indefinite integral was introduced by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1675.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] He adapted the integral symbol, **∫**, from the letter *ſ* (long s), standing for *summa* (written as *ſumma*; Latin for "sum" or "total").
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The modern notation for the definite integral, with limits above and below the integral sign, was first used by Joseph Fourier in *Mémoires* of the French Academy around 1819–1820, reprinted in his book of 1822.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Isaac Newton used a small vertical bar above a variable to indicate integration, or placed the variable inside a box.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The vertical bar was easily confused with **.***x* or *x*′, which are used to indicate differentiation, and the box notation was difficult for printers to reproduce, so these notations were not widely adopted.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The term was first printed in Latin by Jacob Bernoulli in 1690: "Ergo et horum Integralia aequantur".
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The integral symbol ∫ represents integration.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The symbol *dx*, called the differential of the variable *x*, indicates that the variable of integration is *x*.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The function *f*(*x*) is called the *integrand*, the points *a* and *b* are called the limits (or bounds) of integration, and the integral is said to be over the interval [*a*, *b*], called the interval of integration.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] A function is said to be *integrable* if its integral is well-defined and finite.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] the integral is called an indefinite integral, which represents a class of functions (the antiderivative) whose derivative is the integrand.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The fundamental theorem of calculus relates the evaluation of definite integrals to indefinite integrals.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] There are several extensions of the notation for integrals to encompass integration on unbounded domains and/or in multiple dimensions (see later sections of this article).
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In advanced settings, it is not uncommon to leave out *dx* when only the simple Riemann integral is being used, or the exact type of integral is immaterial.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Integrals appear in many practical situations.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] For instance, from the length, width and depth of a swimming pool which is rectangular with a flat bottom, one can determine the volume of water it can contain, the area of its surface, and the length of its edge.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] But if it is oval with a rounded bottom, integrals are required to find exact and rigorous values for these quantities.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In each case, one may divide the sought quantity into infinitely many infinitesimal pieces, then sum the pieces to achieve an accurate approximation.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Alternatively, when replacing these subintervals by ones with the left end height of each piece, the approximation one gets is too low: with twelve such subintervals the approximated area is only 0.6203.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] However, when the number of pieces increases to infinity, it will reach a limit which is the exact value of the area sought (in this case, 2/3).
[src:calculus/integral-p01] which means 2/3 is the result of a weighted sum of function values, √*x*, multiplied by the infinitesimal step widths, denoted by *dx*, on the interval [0, 1].
[src:calculus/integral-p01] There are many ways of formally defining an integral, not all of which are equivalent.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The differences exist mostly to deal with differing special cases which may not be integrable under other definitions, but are also occasionally for pedagogical reasons.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The most commonly used definitions are Riemann integrals and Lebesgue integrals.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The Riemann integral is defined in terms of Riemann sums of functions with respect to *tagged partitions* of an interval.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] This partitions the interval [*a*, *b*] into n sub-intervals [*x**i*−1, *x**i*] indexed by i, each of which is "tagged" with a specific point *t**i* ∈ [*x**i*−1, *x**i*].
[src:calculus/integral-p01] thus each term of the sum is the area of a rectangle with height equal to the function value at the chosen point of the given sub-interval, and width the same as the width of sub-interval, Δ*i* = *x**i*−*x**i*−1.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The *mesh* of such a tagged partition is the width of the largest sub-interval formed by the partition, max*i*=1...*n* Δ*i*.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] When the chosen tags are the maximum (respectively, minimum) value of the function in each interval, the Riemann sum becomes an upper (respectively, lower) Darboux sum, suggesting the close connection between the Riemann integral and the Darboux integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] It is often of interest, both in theory and applications, to be able to pass to the limit under the integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] For instance, a sequence of functions can frequently be constructed that approximate, in a suitable sense, the solution to a problem.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Then the integral of the solution function should be the limit of the integrals of the approximations.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] However, many functions that can be obtained as limits are not Riemann-integrable, and so such limit theorems do not hold with the Riemann integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Therefore, it is of great importance to have a definition of the integral that allows a wider class of functions to be integrated.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Such an integral is the Lebesgue integral, that exploits the following fact to enlarge the class of integrable functions: if the values of a function are rearranged over the domain, the integral of a function should remain the same.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] As Folland puts it, "To compute the Riemann integral of f, one partitions the domain [*a*, *b*] into subintervals", while in the Lebesgue integral, "one is in effect partitioning the range of f ".
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The definition of the Lebesgue integral thus begins with a measure, μ.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In the simplest case, the Lebesgue measure *μ*(*A*) of an interval *A* = [*a*, *b*] is its width, *b* − *a*, so that the Lebesgue integral agrees with the (proper) Riemann integral when both exist.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In more complicated cases, the sets being measured can be highly fragmented, with no continuity and no resemblance to intervals.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Using the "partitioning the range of f " philosophy, the integral of a non-negative function *f* : **R** → **R** should be the sum over t of the areas between a thin horizontal strip between *y* = *t* and *y* = *t* + *dt*.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] where the integral on the right is an ordinary improper Riemann integral (*f*∗ is a strictly decreasing positive function, and therefore has a well-defined improper Riemann integral).
[src:calculus/integral-p01] For a suitable class of functions (the measurable functions) this defines the Lebesgue integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] is a linear functional on this vector space.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] More generally, consider the vector space of all measurable functions on a measure space (*E*,*μ*), taking values in a locally compact complete topological vector space V over a locally compact topological field *K*, *f* : *E* → *V*.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] that is compatible with linear combinations.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In this situation, the linearity holds for the subspace of functions whose integral is an element of V (i.e.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The most important special cases arise when K is **R**, **C**, or a finite extension of the field **Q***p* of p-adic numbers, and V is a finite-dimensional vector space over K, and when *K* = **C** and V is a complex Hilbert space.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Linearity, together with some natural continuity properties and normalization for a certain class of "simple" functions, may be used to give an alternative definition of the integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] This is the approach of Daniell for the case of real-valued functions on a set X, generalized by Nicolas Bourbaki to functions with values in a locally compact topological vector space.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] See Hildebrandt 1953 for an axiomatic characterization of the integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] A number of general inequalities hold for Riemann-integrable functions defined on a closed and bounded interval [*a*, *b*] and can be generalized to other notions of integral (Lebesgue and Daniell).
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In this section, f is a real-valued Riemann-integrable function.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] over an interval [*a*, *b*] is defined if *a* < *b*.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] This means that the upper and lower sums of the function f are evaluated on a partition *a* = *x*0 ≤ *x*1 ≤ . . . ≤ *x**n* = *b* whose values *x**i* are increasing.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Geometrically, this signifies that integration takes place "left to right", evaluating f within intervals [*x* *i* , *x* *i* +1] where an interval with a higher index lies to the right of one with a lower index.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The values a and b, the end-points of the interval, are called the limits of integration of f.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The first convention is necessary in consideration of taking integrals over subintervals of [*a*, *b*]; the second says that an integral taken over a degenerate interval, or a point, should be zero.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] is then well-defined for any cyclic permutation of a, b, and c.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The *fundamental theorem of calculus* is the statement that differentiation and integration are inverse operations: if a continuous function is first integrated and then differentiated, the original function is retrieved.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] An important consequence, sometimes called the *second fundamental theorem of calculus*, allows one to compute integrals by using an antiderivative of the function to be integrated.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Let f be a real-valued function defined on a closed interval [*a*, *b*] that admits an antiderivative F on [*a*, *b*].
[src:calculus/integral-p01] A "proper" Riemann integral assumes the integrand is defined and finite on a closed and bounded interval, bracketed by the limits of integration.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] An improper integral occurs when one or more of these conditions is not satisfied.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In some cases such integrals may be defined by considering the limit of a sequence of proper Riemann integrals on progressively larger intervals.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] That is, the improper integral is the limit of proper integrals as one endpoint of the interval of integration approaches either a specified real number, or ∞, or −∞.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In more complicated cases, limits are required at both endpoints, or at interior points.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] where the differential *dA* indicates that integration is taken with respect to area.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] This double integral can be defined using Riemann sums, and represents the (signed) volume under the graph of *z* = *f*(*x*,*y*) over the domain *R*.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] This reduces the problem of computing a double integral to computing one-dimensional integrals.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Integration over more general domains is possible.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The concept of an integral can be extended to more general domains of integration, such as curved lines and surfaces inside higher-dimensional spaces.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Such integrals are known as line integrals and surface integrals respectively.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] These have important applications in physics, as when dealing with vector fields.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] A *line integral* (sometimes called a *path integral*) is an integral where the function to be integrated is evaluated along a curve.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Various different line integrals are in use.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In the case of a closed curve it is also called a *contour integral*.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The function to be integrated may be a scalar field or a vector field.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The value of the line integral is the sum of values of the field at all points on the curve, weighted by some scalar function on the curve (commonly arc length or, for a vector field, the scalar product of the vector field with a differential vector in the curve).
[src:calculus/integral-p01] This weighting distinguishes the line integral from simpler integrals defined on intervals.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] For an object moving along a path *C* in a vector field **F** such as an electric field or gravitational field, the total work done by the field on the object is obtained by summing up the differential work done in moving from **s** to **s** + *d***s**.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] A *surface integral* generalizes double integrals to integration over a surface (which may be a curved set in space); it can be thought of as the double integral analog of the line integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The value of the surface integral is the sum of the field at all points on the surface.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] This can be achieved by splitting the surface into surface elements, which provide the partitioning for Riemann sums.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] For an example of applications of surface integrals, consider a vector field **v** on a surface *S*; that is, for each point *x* in *S*, **v**(*x*) is a vector.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Imagine that a fluid flows through *S*, such that **v**(*x*) determines the velocity of the fluid at x.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The flux is defined as the quantity of fluid flowing through *S* in unit amount of time.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The fluid flux in this example may be from a physical fluid such as water or air, or from electrical or magnetic flux.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Thus surface integrals have applications in physics, particularly with the classical theory of electromagnetism.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In complex analysis, the integrand is a complex-valued function of a complex variable z instead of a real function of a real variable x.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] A differential form is a mathematical concept in the fields of multivariable calculus, differential topology, and tensors.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Differential forms are organized by degree.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] where *E*, *F*, *G* are functions in three dimensions.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] A differential one-form can be integrated over an oriented path, and the resulting integral is just another way of writing a line integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Here the basic differentials *dx*, *dy*, *dz* measure infinitesimal oriented lengths parallel to the three coordinate axes.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Here the basic two-forms d x ∧ d y , d z ∧ d x , d y ∧ d z {\displaystyle dx\wedge dy,dz\wedge dx,dy\wedge dz} ({\displaystyle dx\wedge dy,dz\wedge dx,dy\wedge dz}) measure oriented areas parallel to the coordinate two-planes.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The symbol ∧ {\displaystyle \wedge } ({\displaystyle \wedge }) denotes the wedge product, which is similar to the cross product in the sense that the wedge product of two forms representing oriented lengths represents an oriented area.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] A two-form can be integrated over an oriented surface, and the resulting integral is equivalent to the surface integral giving the flux of E i + F j + G k {\displaystyle E\mathbf {i} +F\mathbf {j} +G\mathbf {k} } ({\displaystyle E\mathbf {i} +F\mathbf {j} +G\mathbf {k} }).
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Unlike the cross product, and the three-dimensional vector calculus, the wedge product and the calculus of differential forms makes sense in arbitrary dimension and on more general manifolds (curves, surfaces, and their higher-dimensional analogs).
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The exterior derivative plays the role of the gradient and curl of vector calculus, and Stokes' theorem simultaneously generalizes the three theorems of vector calculus: the divergence theorem, Green's theorem, and the Kelvin-Stokes theorem.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The discrete equivalent of integration is summation.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Summations and integrals can be put on the same foundations using the theory of Lebesgue integrals or time-scale calculus.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] An integration that is performed not over a variable (or, in physics, over a space or time dimension), but over a space of functions, is referred to as a functional integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Integrals are used extensively in many areas.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] For example, in probability theory, integrals are used to determine the probability of some random variable falling within a certain range.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Moreover, the integral under an entire probability density function must equal 1, which provides a test of whether a function with no negative values could be a density function or not.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Integrals can be used for computing the area of a two-dimensional region that has a curved boundary, as well as computing the volume of a three-dimensional object that has a curved boundary.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The area of a two-dimensional region can be calculated using the aforementioned definite integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] The volume of a three-dimensional object such as a disc or washer can be computed by disc integration using the equation for the volume of a cylinder, π r 2 h {\displaystyle \pi r^{2}h} ({\displaystyle \pi r^{2}h}), where r {\displaystyle r} ({\displaystyle r}) is the radius.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] In the case of a simple disc created by rotating a curve about the *x*-axis, the radius is given by *f*(*x*), and its height is the differential *dx*.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] where v ( t ) {\displaystyle v(t)} ({\displaystyle v(t)}) is the velocity expressed as a function of time.
[src:calculus/integral-p01] Integrals are also used in thermodynamics, where thermodynamic integration is used to calculate the difference in free energy between two given states.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The most basic technique for computing definite integrals of one real variable is based on the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Let *f*(*x*) be the function of x to be integrated over a given interval [*a*, *b*].
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Then, find an antiderivative of f; that is, a function F such that *F*′ = *f* on the interval.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Sometimes it is necessary to use one of the many techniques that have been developed to evaluate integrals.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Most of these techniques rewrite one integral as a different one which is hopefully more tractable.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Techniques include integration by substitution, integration by parts, integration by trigonometric substitution, and integration by partial fractions.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Alternative methods exist to compute more complex integrals.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Many nonelementary integrals can be expanded in a Taylor series and integrated term by term.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Occasionally, the resulting infinite series can be summed analytically.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The method of convolution using Meijer G-functions can also be used, assuming that the integrand can be written as a product of Meijer G-functions.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] There are also many less common ways of calculating definite integrals; for instance, Parseval's identity can be used to transform an integral over a rectangular region into an infinite sum.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Occasionally, an integral can be evaluated by a trick; for an example of this, see Gaussian integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Computations of volumes of solids of revolution can usually be done with disk integration or shell integration.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Specific results which have been worked out by various techniques are collected in the list of integrals.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Many problems in mathematics, physics, and engineering involve integration where an explicit formula for the integral is desired.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Extensive tables of integrals have been compiled and published over the years for this purpose.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] With the spread of computers, many professionals, educators, and students have turned to computer algebra systems that are specifically designed to perform difficult or tedious tasks, including integration.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Symbolic integration has been one of the motivations for the development of the first such systems, like Macsyma and Maple.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The Risch algorithm provides a general criterion to determine whether the antiderivative of an elementary function is elementary and to compute the integral if is elementary.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] However, functions with closed expressions of antiderivatives are the exception, and consequently, computerized algebra systems have no hope of being able to find an antiderivative for a randomly constructed elementary function.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The Risch algorithm, implemented in Mathematica, Maple and other computer algebra systems, does just that for functions and antiderivatives built from rational functions, radicals, logarithm, and exponential functions.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Some special integrands occur often enough to warrant special study.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] In particular, it may be useful to have, in the set of antiderivatives, the special functions (like the Legendre functions, the hypergeometric function, the gamma function, the incomplete gamma function and so on).
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Extending Risch's algorithm to include such functions is possible but challenging and has been an active research subject.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] More recently a new approach has emerged, using *D*-finite functions, which are the solutions of linear differential equations with polynomial coefficients.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Most of the elementary and special functions are *D*-finite, and the integral of a *D*-finite function is also a *D*-finite function.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] This provides an algorithm to express the antiderivative of a *D*-finite function as the solution of a differential equation.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] This theory also allows one to compute the definite integral of a *D*-function as the sum of a series given by the first coefficients and provides an algorithm to compute any coefficient.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Rule-based integration systems facilitate integration.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Rubi, a computer algebra system rule-based integrator, pattern matches an extensive system of symbolic integration rules to integrate a wide variety of integrands.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] This system uses over 6600 integration rules to compute integrals.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The method of brackets is a generalization of Ramanujan's master theorem that can be applied to a wide range of univariate and multivariate integrals.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] A set of rules are applied to the coefficients and exponential terms of the integrand's power series expansion to determine the integral.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The method is closely related to the Mellin transform.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Definite integrals may be approximated using several methods of numerical integration.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The rectangle method relies on dividing the region under the function into a series of rectangles corresponding to function values and multiplies by the step width to find the sum.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] A better approach, the trapezoidal rule, replaces the rectangles used in a Riemann sum with trapezoids.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The trapezoidal rule weights the first and last values by one half, then multiplies by the step width to obtain a better approximation.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The idea behind the trapezoidal rule, that more accurate approximations to the function yield better approximations to the integral, can be carried further: Simpson's rule approximates the integrand by a piecewise quadratic function.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Riemann sums, the trapezoidal rule, and Simpson's rule are examples of a family of quadrature rules called the Newton–Cotes formulas.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The degree n Newton–Cotes quadrature rule approximates the polynomial on each subinterval by a degree *n* polynomial.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] This polynomial is chosen to interpolate the values of the function on the interval.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Higher degree Newton–Cotes approximations can be more accurate, but they require more function evaluations, and they can suffer from numerical inaccuracy due to Runge's phenomenon.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] One solution to this problem is Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature, in which the integrand is approximated by expanding it in terms of Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Romberg's method halves the step widths incrementally, giving trapezoid approximations denoted by *T*(*h*0), *T*(*h*1), and so on, where *h**k*+1 is half of *h**k*.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] For each new step size, only half the new function values need to be computed; the others carry over from the previous size.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] It then interpolate a polynomial through the approximations, and extrapolate to *T*(0).
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Gaussian quadrature evaluates the function at the roots of a set of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] An n-point Gaussian method is exact for polynomials of degree up to 2*n* − 1.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The computation of higher-dimensional integrals (for example, volume calculations) makes important use of such alternatives as Monte Carlo integration.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The area of an arbitrary two-dimensional shape can be determined using a measuring instrument called planimeter.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] The volume of irregular objects can be measured with precision by the fluid displaced as the object is submerged.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Area can sometimes be found via geometrical compass-and-straightedge constructions of an equivalent square.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Kempf, Jackson and Morales demonstrated mathematical relations that allow an integral to be calculated by means of differentiation.
[src:calculus/integral-p02] Their calculus involves the Dirac delta function and the partial derivative operator ∂ x {\displaystyle \partial _{x}} ({\displaystyle \partial _{x}}).
[src:calculus/integral-p02] This can also be applied to functional integrals, allowing them to be computed by functional differentiation.
[src:calculus/integral] Alhazen determined the equations to calculate the area enclosed by the curve represented by $y=x^{k}$ (which translates to the integral $\int x^{k}\,dx$ in contemporary notation), for any given non-negative integer value of k .
[src:calculus/integral] For instance, one might write ${\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}(c_{1}f+c_{2}g)=c_{1}\int _{a}^{b}f+c_{2}\int _{a}^{b}g}$ to express the linearity of the integral, a property shared by the Riemann integral and all generalizations thereof.
[src:calculus/integral] Here the basic two-forms $dx\wedge dy,dz\wedge dx,dy\wedge dz$ measure oriented areas parallel to the coordinate two-planes.
[src:calculus/integral] The symbol $\wedge$ denotes the wedge product, which is similar to the cross product in the sense that the wedge product of two forms representing oriented lengths represents an oriented area.
[src:calculus/integral] A two-form can be integrated over an oriented surface, and the resulting integral is equivalent to the surface integral giving the flux of $E\mathbf {i} +F\mathbf {j} +G\mathbf {k}$ .
[src:calculus/integral] The volume of a three-dimensional object such as a disc or washer can be computed by disc integration using the equation for the volume of a cylinder, $\pi r^{2}h$ , where r is the radius.
[src:calculus/integral] Using an integral with bounds *a* and *b*, the volume of the disc is equal to: $\pi \int _{a}^{b}f^{2}(x)\,dx.$ Integrals are also used in physics, in areas like kinematics to find quantities like displacement, time, and velocity.
[src:calculus/integral] where $v(t)$ is the velocity expressed as a function of time.
[src:calculus/integral] Their calculus involves the Dirac delta function and the partial derivative operator $\partial _{x}$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In mathematics, a **limit** is the value that a function (or sequence) approaches as the argument (or index) approaches some value.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Limits of functions are essential to calculus and mathematical analysis, and are used to define continuity, derivatives, and integrals.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The concept of a limit of a sequence is further generalized to the concept of a limit of a topological net, and is closely related to limit and direct limit in category theory.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The limit inferior and limit superior provide generalizations of the concept of a limit which are particularly relevant when the limit at a point may not exist.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In formulas, a limit of a function is usually written as $\lim _{x\to c}f(x)=L,$ and is read as "the limit of f of x as x approaches c equals L ".
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This means that the value of the function f can be made arbitrarily close to L , by choosing x sufficiently close to c .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] which reads " f of x tends to L as x tends to c ".
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In the Scholium to *Principia* in 1687, Isaac Newton had a clear definition of a limit, stating that "Those ultimate ratios ... are not actually ratios of ultimate quantities, but limits ... which they can approach so closely that their difference is less than any given quantity".
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Bruce Pourciau further argues that, in addition to Newton actually having a more sophisticated understanding of limits than he is generally credited with, he also provided the first epsilon argument.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The modern definition of a limit goes back to Bernard Bolzano who, in 1817, developed the basics of the epsilon-delta technique to define continuous functions.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] However, his work remained unknown to other mathematicians until thirty years after his death.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Augustin-Louis Cauchy in 1821, followed by Karl Weierstrass, formalized the definition of the limit of a function which became known as the (ε, δ)-definition of limit.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The modern notation of placing the arrow below the limit symbol was invented by John Gaston Leathem in 1905 and popularized by G.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Hardy's 1908 textbook *A Course of Pure Mathematics*.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A sequence of real numbers $a_{0},a_{1},\dots$ is said to converge to a limit L if the terms of the sequence give an arbitrarily good approximation of the number L , after discarding finitely many initial terms.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Each term in the sequence is an approximation to the rational number $1/3=0.333\ldots$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] If an approximation is desired that lies within a given error $\epsilon$ , then all of the terms of the sequence except finitely many lie within the target error.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] For example, to get within $\epsilon =0.001$ of $1/3$ , the approximations 0 , $0.3$ , and $0.33$ are outside the error window, but after discarding those three approximations, *all* of the remaining approximations are within the error range $\epsilon =0.001$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The same approximation property holds for every positive error $\epsilon$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] If such an L does not exist, $\{a_{n}\}_{n\in \mathbb {N} }$ is said to be *divergent*.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A sequence is said to *tend to infinity* if all but finitely many terms exceed each given number.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] An example is the sequence $1,2,3,\ldots$ of positive integers.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This tends to infinity because, for any given bound M , every element of the sequence is greater than M after discarding the finite number that are not.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Formally, $\{a_{n}\}_{n\in \mathbb {N} }$ tends to infinity if, given any real M , there exists a positive integer N such that $a_{n}>M$ for every $n>N$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This is written as $\lim _{n\to \infty }a_{n}=\infty$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Similarly, the sequence is said to *tend to negative infinity* if all but finitely many terms are less than any given lower bound.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This is written as $\lim _{n\to \infty }a_{n}=-\infty$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In each case where $\lim _{n\to \infty }a_{n}=\infty$ or $\lim _{n\to \infty }a_{n}=-\infty$ , the sequence is said to have an infinite limit.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] But it does not have a limit in the sense of being convergent to a real number, since $\infty$ and $-\infty$ are not real numbers.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The discussion of sequences above is for sequences of real numbers.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The notion of limits can be defined for sequences valued in more abstract spaces, such as metric spaces.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In some sense the *most* abstract space in which limits can be defined are topological spaces.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] If X is a topological space with topology $\tau$ , and $\{a_{n}\}_{n\geq 0}$ is a sequence in X , then the limit (when it exists) of the sequence is a point $a\in X$ such that, given a (open) neighborhood $U\in \tau$ of a , there exists an N such that for every $n>N$ , $a_{n}\in U$ is satisfied.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In this case, the limit (if it exists) may not be unique.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] However it must be unique if X is a Hausdorff space.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This section deals with the idea of limits of sequences of functions, not to be confused with the idea of limits of functions, discussed below.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The field of functional analysis partly seeks to identify useful notions of convergence on function spaces.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] For example, consider the space of functions from a generic set E to $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Then the sequence $f_{n}$ is said to converge pointwise to f .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] However, such sequences can exhibit unexpected behavior.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] For example, it is possible to construct a sequence of continuous functions which has a discontinuous pointwise limit.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Another notion of convergence is uniform convergence.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The uniform distance between two functions $f,g:E\rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ is the maximum difference between the two functions as the argument $x\in E$ is varied.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] That is, $d(f,g)=\max _{x\in E}|f(x)-g(x)|.$ Then the sequence $f_{n}$ is said to **uniformly converge** or have a **uniform limit** of f if $f_{n}\rightarrow f$ with respect to this distance.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The uniform limit has "nicer" properties than the pointwise limit.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] For example, the uniform limit of a sequence of continuous functions is continuous.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Many different notions of convergence can be defined on function spaces.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This is sometimes dependent on the regularity of the space.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Prominent examples of function spaces with some notion of convergence are Lp spaces and Sobolev space.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Suppose f is a real-valued function and c is a real number.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] means that *f*(*x*) can be made to be as close to L as desired, by making x sufficiently close to c.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In that case, the above equation can be read as "the limit of f of x, as x approaches c, is L".
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Formally, the definition of the "limit of $f(x)$ as x approaches c " is given as follows.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The limit is a real number L so that, given an arbitrary real number $\varepsilon >0$ (thought of as the "error"), there is a $\delta >0$ such that, for any x satisfying $0<|x-c|<\delta$ , it holds that $|f(x)-L|<\varepsilon$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This is known as the (*ε*, *δ*)-definition of limit.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The inequality $0<|x-c|$ is used to exclude c from the set of points under consideration, but some authors do not include this in their definition of limits, replacing $0<|x-c|<\delta$ with simply $|x-c|<\delta$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This replacement is equivalent to additionally requiring that f be continuous at c .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] It can be proven that there is an equivalent definition which makes manifest the connection between limits of sequences and limits of functions.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The equivalent definition is given as follows.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] First observe that for every sequence $\{x_{n}\}$ in the domain of f , there is an associated sequence $\{f(x_{n})\}$ , the image of the sequence under f .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The limit is a real number L so that, for *all* sequences $x_{n}\rightarrow c$ , the associated sequence $f(x_{n})\rightarrow L$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] It is possible to define the notion of having a "left-handed" limit ("from below"), and a notion of a "right-handed" limit ("from above").
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] An example is given by the positive indicator function, $f:\mathbb {R} \rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ , defined such that $f(x)=0$ if $x\leq 0$ , and $f(x)=1$ if $x>0$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] At $x=0$ , the function has a "left-handed limit" of 0, a "right-handed limit" of 1, and its limit does not exist.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] or it can be defined directly: the "limit of f as x tends to positive infinity" is defined as a value L such that, given any real $\varepsilon >0$ , there exists an $M>0$ so that for all $x>M$ , $|f(x)-L|<\varepsilon$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The definition for sequences is equivalent: As $n\rightarrow +\infty$ , we have $f(x_{n})\rightarrow L$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In these expressions, the infinity is normally considered to be signed ( $+\infty$ or $-\infty$ ) and corresponds to a one-sided limit of the reciprocal.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A two-sided infinite limit can be defined, but an author would explicitly write $\pm \infty$ to be clear.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Or a direct definition can be given as follows: given any real number $M>0$ , there is a $\delta >0$ so that for $0<|x-c|<\delta$ , the absolute value of the function $|f(x)|>M$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A sequence can also have an infinite limit: as $n\rightarrow \infty$ , the sequence $f(x_{n})\rightarrow \infty$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This direct definition is easier to extend to one-sided infinite limits.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] While mathematicians do talk about functions approaching limits "from above" or "from below", there is not a standard mathematical notation for this as there is for one-sided limits.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In non-standard analysis (which involves a hyperreal enlargement of the number system), the limit of a sequence $(a_{n})$ can be expressed as the standard part of the value $a_{H}$ of the natural extension of the sequence at an infinite hypernatural index *n* = *H*.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Thus, $\lim _{n\to \infty }a_{n}=\operatorname {st} (a_{H}).$ Here, the standard part function "st" rounds off each finite hyperreal number to the nearest real number (the difference between them is infinitesimal).
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This formalizes the natural intuition that for "very large" values of the index, the terms in the sequence are "very close" to the limit value of the sequence.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Let $\{a_{n}\}_{n>0}$ be a sequence in a topological space X .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] For concreteness, X can be thought of as $\mathbb {R}$ , but the definitions hold more generally.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The limit set is the set of points such that if there is a convergent subsequence $\{a_{n_{k}}\}_{k>0}$ with $a_{n_{k}}\rightarrow a$ , then a belongs to the limit set.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In this context, such an a is sometimes called a limit point.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A use of this notion is to characterize the "long-term behavior" of oscillatory sequences.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Starting from n=1, the first few terms of this sequence are $-1,+1,-1,+1,\cdots$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] It can be checked that it is oscillatory, so has no limit, but has limit points $\{-1,+1\}$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This notion is used in dynamical systems, to study limits of trajectories.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Defining a trajectory to be a function $\gamma :\mathbb {R} \rightarrow X$ , the point $\gamma (t)$ is thought of as the "position" of the trajectory at "time" t .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The limit set of a trajectory is defined as follows.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] To any sequence of increasing times $\{t_{n}\}$ , there is an associated sequence of positions $\{x_{n}\}=\{\gamma (t_{n})\}$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] If x is the limit set of the sequence $\{x_{n}\}$ for any sequence of increasing times, then x is a limit set of the trajectory.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Technically, this is the $\omega$ -limit set.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The corresponding limit set for sequences of decreasing time is called the $\alpha$ -limit set.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] An illustrative example is the circle trajectory: $\gamma (t)=(\cos(t),\sin(t))$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This has no unique limit, but for each $\theta \in \mathbb {R}$ , the point $(\cos(\theta ),\sin(\theta ))$ is a limit point, given by the sequence of times $t_{n}=\theta +2\pi n$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] But the limit points need not be attained on the trajectory.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The trajectory $\gamma (t)=t/(1+t)(\cos(t),\sin(t))$ also has the unit circle as its limit set.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Limits are used to define a number of important concepts in analysis.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A particular expression of interest which is formalized as the limit of a sequence is sums of infinite series.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Otherwise, the series is said to be divergent.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A classic example is the Basel problem, where $a_{n}=1/n^{2}$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] However, while for sequences there is essentially a unique notion of convergence, for series there are different notions of convergence.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] This is due to the fact that the expression $\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }a_{n}$ does not discriminate between different orderings of the sequence $\{a_{n}\}$ , while the convergence properties of the sequence of partial sums *can* depend on the ordering of the sequence.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A series which converges for all orderings is called **unconditionally convergent**.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] It can be proven to be equivalent to absolute convergence.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A series is absolutely convergent if $\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }|a_{n}|$ is well defined.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Furthermore, all possible orderings give the same value.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Otherwise, the series is conditionally convergent.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A surprising result for conditionally convergent series is the Riemann series theorem: depending on the ordering, the partial sums can be made to converge to any real number, as well as $\pm \infty$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A useful application of the theory of sums of series is for power series.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] These are sums of series of the form $f(z)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }c_{n}z^{n}.$ Often z is thought of as a complex number, and a suitable notion of convergence of complex sequences is needed.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The set of values of $z\in \mathbb {C}$ for which the series sum converges is a circle, with its radius known as the radius of convergence.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The definition of continuity at a point is given through limits.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The above definition of a limit is true even if $f(c)\neq L$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Indeed, the function *f* need not even be defined at c.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] However, if $f(c)$ is defined and is equal to L , then the function is said to be **continuous at the point** c .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Equivalently, the function is continuous at c if $f(x)\rightarrow f(c)$ as $x\rightarrow c$ , or in terms of sequences, whenever $x_{n}\rightarrow c$ , then $f(x_{n})\rightarrow f(c)$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] An example of a limit where f is not defined at c is given below.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Thus, *f*(*x*) can be made arbitrarily close to the limit of 2—just by making x sufficiently close to 1.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In addition to limits at finite values, functions can also have limits at infinity.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] As x becomes extremely large, the value of *f*(*x*) approaches 2, and the value of *f*(*x*) can be made as close to 2 as one could wish—by making x sufficiently large.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] An important class of functions when considering limits are continuous functions.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] These are precisely those functions which *preserve limits*, in the sense that if f is a continuous function, then whenever $a_{n}\rightarrow a$ in the domain of f , then the limit $f(a_{n})$ exists and furthermore is $f(a)$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Let $f:X\rightarrow Y$ be a continuous function between topological spaces X and Y .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] By definition, for each open set V in Y , the preimage $f^{-1}(V)$ is open in X .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Now suppose $a_{n}\rightarrow a$ is a sequence with limit a in X .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Then $f(a_{n})$ is a sequence in Y , and $f(a)$ is some point.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Then $f^{-1}(V)$ is an open set (by continuity of f ) which in particular contains a , and therefore $f^{-1}(V)$ is a neighborhood of a .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] By the convergence of $a_{n}$ to a , there exists an N such that for $n>N$ , we have $a_{n}\in f^{-1}(V)$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Then applying f to both sides gives that, for the same N , for each $n>N$ we have $f(a_{n})\in V$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Originally V was an arbitrary neighborhood of $f(a)$ , so $f(a_{n})\rightarrow f(a)$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In real analysis, for the more concrete case of real-valued functions defined on a subset $E\subset \mathbb {R}$ , that is, $f:E\rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ , a continuous function may also be defined as a function which is continuous at every point of its domain.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In topology, limits are used to define limit points of a subset of a topological space, which in turn give a useful characterization of closed sets.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In a topological space X , consider a subset S .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A point a is called a limit point if there is a sequence $\{a_{n}\}$ in $S\setminus \{a\}$ such that $a_{n}\rightarrow a$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The reason why $\{a_{n}\}$ is defined to be in $S\setminus \{a\}$ rather than just S is illustrated by the following example.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Then $2\in S$ , and therefore is the limit of the constant sequence $2,2,\cdots$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A closed set, which is defined to be the complement of an open set, is equivalently any set C which contains all its limit points.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The derivative is defined formally as a limit.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In the scope of real analysis, the derivative is first defined for real functions f defined on a subset $E\subset \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The derivative at $x\in E$ is defined as follows.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] If the limit of ${\frac {f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}}$ as $h\rightarrow 0$ exists, then the derivative at x is this limit.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] If the derivative exists, it is commonly denoted by $f'(x)$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] For sequences of real numbers, a number of properties can be proven.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Suppose $\{a_{n}\}$ and $\{b_{n}\}$ are two sequences converging to a and b respectively.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Equivalently, the function $f(x)=1/x$ is continuous about nonzero x .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A property of convergent sequences of real numbers is that they are Cauchy sequences.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Informally, for any arbitrarily small error $\varepsilon$ , it is possible to find an interval of diameter $\varepsilon$ such that eventually the sequence is contained within the interval.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Cauchy sequences are closely related to convergent sequences.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In fact, for sequences of real numbers they are equivalent: any Cauchy sequence is convergent.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In general metric spaces, it continues to hold that convergent sequences are also Cauchy.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] But the converse is not true: not every Cauchy sequence is convergent in a general metric space.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A classic counterexample is the rational numbers, $\mathbb {Q}$ , with the usual distance.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The sequence of decimal approximations to ${\sqrt {2}}$ , truncated at the n th decimal place is a Cauchy sequence, but *does not converge in* $\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A metric space in which every Cauchy sequence is also convergent, that is, Cauchy sequences are equivalent to convergent sequences, is known as a complete metric space.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] One reason Cauchy sequences can be "easier to work with" than convergent sequences is that they are a property of the sequence $\{a_{n}\}$ alone, while convergent sequences require not just the sequence $\{a_{n}\}$ but also the limit of the sequence a .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Beyond whether or not a sequence $\{a_{n}\}$ converges to a limit a , it is possible to describe how fast a sequence converges to a limit.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] One way to quantify this is using the order of convergence of a sequence.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] A formal definition of order of convergence can be stated as follows.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Suppose $\{a_{n}\}_{n>0}$ is a sequence of real numbers which is convergent with limit a .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] If positive constants $\lambda$ and $\alpha$ exist such that $\lim _{n\to \infty }{\frac {\left|a_{n+1}-a\right|}{\left|a_{n}-a\right|^{\alpha }}}=\lambda$ then $a_{n}$ is said to converge to a with **order of convergence** $\alpha$ .
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] The constant $\lambda$ is known as the asymptotic error constant.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Order of convergence is used for example the field of numerical analysis, in error analysis.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] There exist limit expressions whose modulus of convergence is undecidable.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] In recursion theory, the limit lemma proves that it is possible to encode undecidable problems using limits.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] There are several theorems or tests that indicate whether the limit exists.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] Examples include the ratio test and the squeeze theorem.
[src:calculus/limit-mathematics] However they may not tell how to compute the limit.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] In mathematics, a **partial derivative** of a function of several variables is its derivative with respect to one of those variables, with the others held constant (as opposed to the total derivative, in which all variables are allowed to vary).
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] It is the rate of change of the function in the x -direction.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The symbol used to denote partial derivatives is ∂.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] One of the first known uses of this symbol in mathematics is by Marquis de Condorcet from 1770, who used it for partial differences.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The modern partial derivative notation was created by Adrien-Marie Legendre (1786), although he later abandoned it; Carl Gustav Jacob Jacobi reintroduced the symbol in 1841.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Like ordinary derivatives, the partial derivative is defined as a limit.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Let U be an open subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and $f:U\to \mathbb {R}$ a function.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] where $\mathbf {e_{i}}$ is the unit vector of i-th variable *x**i*.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] In fact, the last equality shows that the partial derivative is just the directional derivative where the direction is the i -th standard basis vector.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Even if all partial derivatives $\partial f/\partial x_{i}(a)$ exist at a given point a, the function need not be continuous there.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] However, if all partial derivatives exist in a neighborhood of a and are continuous there, then f is totally differentiable in that neighborhood and the total derivative is continuous.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] In this case, it is said that f is a *C*1 function.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] This can be used to generalize for vector valued functions, $f:U\to \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ , by carefully using a component-wise argument.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The partial derivative ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial f}{\partial x}}}$ is itself a function defined on U and can be partially-differentiated again.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] If the direction of derivative is *not* repeated, it is called a ***mixed partial derivative***.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] For the following examples, let f be a function in x, y, and z.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] When dealing with functions of multiple variables, some of these variables may be related to each other, thus it may be necessary to specify explicitly which variables are being held constant to avoid ambiguity.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Conventionally, for clarity and simplicity of notation, the partial derivative *function* and the *value* of the function at a specific point are conflated by including the function arguments when the partial derivative symbol (Leibniz notation) is used.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] might be used for the value of the function at the point $(x,y,z)=(u,v,w)$ .
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] However, this convention breaks down when we want to evaluate the partial derivative at a point like $(x,y,z)=(17,u+v,v^{2})$ .
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Thus, in these cases, it may be preferable to use the Euler differential operator notation with $D_{i}$ as the partial derivative symbol with respect to the i-th variable.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] For instance, one would write $D_{1}f(17,u+v,v^{2})$ for the example described above, while the expression $D_{1}f$ represents the partial derivative *function* with respect to the first variable.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] For higher order partial derivatives, the partial derivative (function) of $D_{i}f$ with respect to the j-th variable is denoted $D_{j}(D_{i}f)=D_{i,j}f$ .
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] That is, $D_{j}\circ D_{i}=D_{i,j}$ , so that the variables are listed in the order in which the derivatives are taken, and thus, in reverse order of how the composition of operators is usually notated.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Of course, Clairaut's theorem implies that $D_{i,j}=D_{j,i}$ as long as comparatively mild regularity conditions on f are satisfied.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] An important example of a function of several variables is the case of a scalar-valued function $f(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})$ on a domain in Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ (e.g., on $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ or $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ ).
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] In this case f has a partial derivative $\partial f/\partial x_{j}$ with respect to each variable *x**j*.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] This vector is called the *gradient* of f at a.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] If f is differentiable at every point in some domain, then the gradient is a vector-valued function ∇*f* which takes the point a to the vector ∇*f*(*a*).
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Consequently, the gradient produces a vector field.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] This definition is valid in a broad range of contexts, for example, where the norm of a vector is defined.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] In finite dimensions, it does not depend on the choice of norm, since all norms are equivalent.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Its applicability extends to functions on finite-dimensional vector spaces without a metric and to differentiable manifolds, such as in general relativity.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Suppose that f is a function of more than one variable.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The two axes are shown here with different scales.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The graph of this function defines a surface in Euclidean space.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] To every point on this surface, there are an infinite number of tangent lines.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Partial differentiation is the act of choosing one of these lines and finding its slope.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Usually, the lines of most interest are those that are parallel to the xz-plane, and those that are parallel to the yz-plane (which result from holding either y or x constant, respectively).
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] To find the slope of the line tangent to the function at *P*(1, 1) and parallel to the xz-plane, we treat y as a constant.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The graph and this plane are shown on the right.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Below, we see how the function looks on the plane *y* = 1.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] So at (1, 1), by substitution, the slope is 3.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] That is, the partial derivative of z with respect to x at (1, 1) is 3, as shown in the graph.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] In other words, every value of y defines a function, denoted *fy*, which is a function of one variable x.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] In this section the subscript notation *fy* denotes a function contingent on a fixed value of y, and not a partial derivative.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] In this expression, a is a *constant*, not a *variable*, so *fa* is a function of only one real variable, that being x.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The above procedure can be performed for any choice of a.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] This is the partial derivative of f with respect to x.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Here '∂' is a rounded 'd' called the *partial derivative symbol*; to distinguish it from the letter 'd', '∂' is sometimes pronounced "partial".
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Second and higher order partial derivatives are defined analogously to the higher order derivatives of univariate functions.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Schwarz's theorem states that if the second derivatives are continuous, the expression for the cross partial derivative is unaffected by which variable the partial derivative is taken with respect to first and which is taken second.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Own and cross partial derivatives appear in the Hessian matrix which is used in the second order conditions in optimization problems.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] There is a concept for partial derivatives that is analogous to antiderivatives for regular derivatives.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Given a partial derivative, it allows for the partial recovery of the original function.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Here, the constant of integration is no longer a constant, but instead a function of all the variables of the original function except x.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The reason for this is that all the other variables are treated as constant when taking the partial derivative, so any function which does not involve x will disappear when taking the partial derivative, and we have to account for this when we take the antiderivative.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The most general way to represent this is to have the constant represent an unknown function of all the other variables.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Thus the set of functions $x^{2}+xy+g(y)$ , where g is any one-argument function, represents the entire set of functions in variables *x*, *y* that could have produced the x-partial derivative $2x+y$ .
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] If all the partial derivatives of a function are known (for example, with the gradient), then the antiderivatives can be matched via the above process to reconstruct the original function up to a constant.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Unlike in the single-variable case, however, not every set of functions can be the set of all (first) partial derivatives of a single function.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] In other words, not every vector field is conservative.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] which represents the rate with which a cone's volume changes if its radius is varied and its height is kept constant.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The partial derivative with respect to h equals ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{3}}\pi r^{2}}$ , which represents the rate with which the volume changes if its height is varied and its radius is kept constant.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The difference between the total and partial derivative is the elimination of indirect dependencies between variables in partial derivatives.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Partial derivatives appear in any calculus-based optimization problem with more than one choice variable.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] For example, in economics a firm may wish to maximize profit π(*x*, *y*) with respect to the choice of the quantities x and y of two different types of output.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The first order conditions for this optimization are π*x* = 0 = π*y*.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Since both partial derivatives π*x* and π*y* will generally themselves be functions of both arguments x and y, these two first order conditions form a system of two equations in two unknowns.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Partial derivatives appear in thermodynamic equations like Gibbs-Duhem equation, in quantum mechanics as in Schrödinger wave equation, as well as in other equations from mathematical physics.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] This equality can be rearranged to have differential quotient of mole fractions on one side.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Partial derivatives are key to target-aware image resizing algorithms.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Widely known as seam carving, these algorithms require each pixel in an image to be assigned a numerical 'energy' to describe their dissimilarity against orthogonal adjacent pixels.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The algorithm then progressively removes rows or columns with the lowest energy.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] The formula established to determine a pixel's energy (magnitude of gradient at a pixel) depends heavily on the constructs of partial derivatives.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] Partial derivatives play a prominent role in economics, in which most functions describing economic behaviour posit that the behaviour depends on more than one variable.
[src:calculus/partial-derivative] For example, a societal consumption function may describe the amount spent on consumer goods as depending on both income and wealth; the marginal propensity to consume is then the partial derivative of the consumption function with respect to income.
